{"title_page": "Bushfires in Australia", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Bushfire|general information on uncontrolled fires in non-urban areas|Wildfire}}\n{{short description|Frequently occurring wildfire events}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:Swifts creek 14-12-2006 1600 -2.jpg|thumb|right|Looking towards the town [[Swifts Creek, Victoria]], in December 2006 during the [[2006-07 Australian bushfire season|Victorian Alpine fires]]]]\n[[File:2003 Bushfires aftermath, Big River near Anglers Rest.jpg|right|thumb|Intense bushfires can seriously impact the environment, such as here by the [[Big River (Victoria)|Big River]], near [[Anglers Rest, Victoria|Anglers Rest]], [[East Gippsland]], after the [[2003 Eastern Victorian alpine bushfires|2003 Victorian fires]]]]\n\n'''Bushfires in Australia''' are a widespread and regular occurrence that have contributed significantly to shaping the nature of the continent over millions of years. Eastern Australia is one of the most fire-prone regions of the world, and its predominant eucalyptus forests have evolved to thrive on the phenomenon of bushfire.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Making Of The Bush: a portrait of the island continent |episode-link= |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7299705?selectedversion=NBD9997404 |access-date=12 February 2020 |series=Nature of Australia |series-link= |first=John |last=Vandenbeld |network=[[ABC TV (Australia)|ABC TV]] |station= |date=1988 |season= |series-no= |number=3 |minutes=55 |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=en-AU}}</ref> However the fires can cause significant property damage and loss of both human and animal life. Bushfires have killed approximately 800 people in Australia since 1851,<ref name=Tronson>{{cite web |last1=Tronson |first1=Mark |title=Bushfires \u2013 across the nation |url=https://www.christiantoday.co.nz/news/bushfires-across-the-nation.html |website=Christian Today|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> and [[1,000,000,000|billions]] of animals.gay\n\nThe most destructive fires are usually preceded by extreme high temperatures, low relative humidity and strong winds, which combine to create ideal conditions for the rapid spread of fire.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\">{{cite news|author=Williams, Liz T.|url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/science-environment/2011/11/the-worst-bushfires-in-australias-history/|title=The worst bushfires in Australia\u2019s history|date=3 November 2011|work=[[Australian Geographic]]|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Severe fire storms are often named according to the day on which they peaked, including the five most deadly blazes: [[Black Saturday bushfires|Black Saturday]] 2009 in Victoria (173 people killed, 2000 homes lost); [[Ash Wednesday bushfires|Ash Wednesday]] 1983 in Victoria and South Australia (75 dead, nearly 1900 homes); [[Black Friday bushfires|Black Friday]] 1939 in Victoria (71 dead, 650 houses destroyed), [[1967 Tasmanian fires|Black Tuesday]] 1967 in Tasmania (62 people and almost 1300 homes); and the [[1925-26 Victorian bushfire season|Gippsland fires and Black Sunday]] of 1926 in Victoria (60 people killed over a two-month period).<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/> Other major [[conflagration]]s include the 1851 [[Black Thursday bushfires]], the [[2006\u201307 Australian bushfire season|2006 December bushfires]], the [[1974-75 Australian bushfire season|1974-75 fires]] that affected 15% of Australia,<ref>{{cite web|title=New South Wales, December 1974 Bushfire - New South Wales|url=https://knowledge.aidr.org.au/resources/bushfire-new-south-wales-1974/|website=Australian Institute for Disaster Resilience|publisher=Government of Australia|accessdate=13 January 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113201506/https://knowledge.aidr.org.au/resources/bushfire-new-south-wales-1974/|archivedate=13 January 2020|quote=During the summer between 1974 and 1975, Australia experienced its worst bushfire season in 30 years. Approximately 15 per cent of Australia's physical land mass sustained extensive fire damage. This equates to roughly around 117 million ha.}}</ref> and the ongoing [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|2019\u201320 bushfires]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/extraordinary-2019-ends-with-deadliest-day-of-the-worst-fire-season-20191231-p53nw0.html|title='Extraordinary' 2019 ends with deadliest day of the worst fire season|date=31 December 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en-AU|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, it was estimated that over 1.25&nbsp;billion animals have died in the [[2019-2020 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/estimated-125-billion-animals-killed-australian-bushfires-2020-jan|title=Estimated 1.25 billion animals killed in Australian bushfires|work=TV10|date=10 January 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe gradual drying of the Australian continent over the last 15 million years has produced an ecology and environment prone to fire, which has resulted in many specialised adaptations amongst [[Flora of Australia|flora]] and [[Fauna of Australia|fauna]]. Some of the country's flora has evolved to rely on bushfires for reproduction. [[Aboriginal Australian]]s used to [[Fire-stick farming|use fire]] to clear grasslands for hunting and to clear tracks through dense vegetation,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The history of fire in Australia \u2014 and how it can help us face the bushfires of the future |episode-link= |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-10/fires-bushfires-in-australia-history-lessons-for-future/11937652 |series=Rear Vision |series-link= |author1=Ross, Monique |author2=Quince, Annabelle |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |station= |date=11 January 2020 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=en-AU |access-date=13 February 2020 }}</ref> and European settlers have also had to adapt to using fire to enhance agriculture and forest management since the 19th century. Fire and forest management has evolved again through the 20th and 21st centuries with the spread of national parks and nature reserves, while human-caused [[global warming]] is predicted to continue increasing the frequency of blazes.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== History ==\n{{See|Eucalyptus#Fire hazard}}\n[[File:Epicormic Shoots from an Epicormic Bud on Eucalyptus following Bushfire 2, near Anglers Rest, Vic, Aust, jjron 27.3.2005.jpg|left|thumb|[[Epicormic shoots]] sprouting vigorously from epicormic buds beneath the thick bushfire damaged [[Bark (botany)|bark]] of a ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' tree \u2013 one of the mechanisms evolved by plants to survive bushfires]]\n[[File:Bushfire damage.jpg|thumb|right|Bushfire damage to forests in [[East Gippsland]], Victoria from the [[2003 Eastern Victorian alpine bushfires]], two years after fires swept through the area, showing the recovery of trees and undergrowth]]\n\n===Before European settlement===\n\nAccording to [[Tim Flannery]] (''[[The Future Eaters]]''), fire is one of the most important forces at work in the Australian environment. Some plants have [[evolution|evolved]] a variety of mechanisms to survive or even require bushfires (possessing [[epicormic shoot]]s or [[lignotuber]]s that sprout after a fire, or developing fire-resistant or fire-triggered [[seed]]s), or even encourage fire ([[eucalypt]]s contain flammable oils in the leaves) as a way to eliminate competition from less fire-tolerant species.<ref>{{cite book|author=White, M. E.|year=1986|title=The Greening of Gondwana|publisher=Reed Books|location=Frenchs Forest, Australia|isbn=|page=}}</ref> Early European explorers of the Australian coastline noted extensive bushfire smoke. [[Abel Janszoon Tasman]]'s expedition saw smoke drifting over the coast of Tasmania in 1642 and noted blackened trunks and baked earth in the forests. While charting the east coast in 1770, Captain Cook's crew saw autumn fires in the bush burning on most days of the voyage.<ref name=Blainey>{{cite book|author=Blainey, Geoffrey|author-link=Geoffrey Blainey|title=The Rise and Fall of Ancient Australia|publisher=Penguin Viking|location=|isbn=|publication-date=2015}}</ref>{{rp|50\u201351}}\n\nThe fires would have been caused by both natural phenomenon and human hands. Aborigines in many regions set fire to grasslands in the hope of producing lusher grass to fatten kangaroos and other game and, at certain times of year, burned fire breaks as a precaution against bushfire.<ref name=Blainey/>{{rp|59}} [[Fire-stick farming]] was also used to facilitate hunting and to promote the growth of bush potatoes and other edible ground-level plants.  In central Australia, they used fire in this way to manage their country for thousands of years.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227223739/http://www.schools.nt.edu.au/tlcland/publications/Fire%20Book.pdf|url=http://www.schools.nt.edu.au/tlcland/publications/Fire%20Book.pdf|title=The Fire Book|publisher=Tangentyre Landcare|year=2005|archive-date=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlannery writes that \"The use of fire by Aboriginal people was so widespread and constant that virtually every early explorer in Australia makes mention of it. It was Aboriginal fire that prompted James Cook to call Australia 'This continent of smoke'.\" However, he goes on to say: \"When control was wrested from the Aborigines and placed in the hands of Europeans, disaster resulted.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=Flannery, Tim|author-link=Tim Flannery|url=https://www.ecobooks.com/books/futureat.htm|title=The Future Eaters: An Ecological History of the Australasian Lands and People|publisher=Grove Press|year=2002|isbn=|page=}}</ref> Fire suppression became the dominant paradigm in fire management leading to a significant shift away from traditional burning practices. A 2001 study found that the disruption of traditional burning practices and the introduction of unrestrained logging meant that many areas of Australia were now prone to extensive wildfires especially in the dry season.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ward, D. J.|author2=Lamont, B. B.|author3=Burrows, C. L.|publication-date=2001|title=Historical role of fire: Grasstrees reveal contrasting fire regimes in eucalypt forest before and after European settlement of southwestern Australia|journal=Forest Ecology and Management|number=150|pages=323\u2013329}}</ref> A similar study in 2017 found that the removal of mature trees by Europeans since they began to settle in Australia may have triggered extensive shrub regeneration which presents a much greater fire fuel hazard.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Relationships between mature trees and fire fuel hazard in Australian forest|first1=Nicholas|last1=Wilson|first2=Geoffrey J.|last2=Cary|first3=Philip|last3=Gibbons|date=15 June 2018|journal=International Journal of Wildland Fire|volume=27|issue=5|pages=353\u2013362|doi=10.1071/WF17112|hdl=1885/160659}}</ref> Another factor was the introduction of [[Andropogon gayanus|gamba grass]] imported into Queensland as a pasture grass in 1942, and planted on a large scale from 1983. This can fuel intense bushfires, leading to loss of tree cover and long-term environmental damage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gamba grass (''Andropogon gayanus'') |url=http://www.daff.qld.gov.au/plants/weeds-pest-animals-ants/weeds/a-z-listing-of-weeds/photo-guide-to-weeds/gamba-grass |work=A\u2013Z listing of weeds: Photo guide to weeds |publisher=Queensland Department of Primary Industries}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Head, Lesley|author1-link=Lesley Head|author2=Atchison, Jennifer|year=2015|title=Governing invasive plants: Policy and practice in managing the Gamba grass (Andropogon gayanus) \u2013 Bushfire nexus in northern Australia|journal=Land Use Policy|number=47|pages=225\u2013234}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:WP Black Thursday.jpg|thumb|400px|A depiction of the 1851 [[Black Thursday bushfires]] in Victoria]]\n\nAustralia's hot, arid climate and wind-driven bushfires were a new and frightening phenomenon to the European settlers of the colonial era. The devastating Victorian bushfires of 1851, remembered as the [[Black Thursday bushfires]], burned in a chain from [[Portland, Victoria|Portland]] to [[Gippsland]], and sent smoke billowing across the Bass Strait to north west Tasmania, where terrified settlers huddled around candles in their huts under a blackened afternoon sky.<ref name=Blainey/>{{rp|386\u2013387}} The fires covered five million hectares (around one quarter of what is now the state of Victoria). Portland, Plenty Ranges, Westernport, the Wimmera and Dandenong districts were badly hit, and around twelve lives were recorded lost, along with one million sheep and thousands of cattle.<ref name=FFM>{{cite web |url=https://www.ffm.vic.gov.au/history-and-incidents/past-bushfires |work=Forest Fire Management Victoria|title=Past bushfires|publisher=Government of Victoria|accessdate=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nNew arrivals from the wetter climes of Britain and Ireland learned painful lessons in fire management and the European farmers slowly began to adapt - growing green crops around their haystacks and burning fire breaks around their pastures, and becoming cautious about burn offs of wheatfield stubble and ringbarked trees.<ref name=Blainey/>{{rp|387}} But major fire events persisted, including South Gippsland's 1898 [[Red Tuesday bushfires]] that burned {{convert|260000|ha}} and claimed twelve lives and more than 2,000 buildings.<ref name=FFM/>\n\n===20th century===\n\nLarge bushfires continued throughout the 20th century. With increasing population and urban spread into bushland came increasing death tolls and property damage during large fires.<ref name=Cheney/>\n\n====1925-6: Gippsland fires and Black Sunday====\n\nDuring the [[1925\u201326 Victorian bushfire season]], large areas of [[Gippsland]] in Victoria caught fire, leading to the Black Sunday fires on 14 February, when 31 people were killed in [[Warburton, Victoria|Warburton]], near Melbourne. These fires remain the fifth most deadly bushfires recorded, with 60 people killed over two months.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/>\n\n====1938-9 season and Black Friday====\n[[File:Black Friday 1939.jpg|thumb|Extent of the 1939 [[Black Friday bushfires]] in Victoria]]\n\nThe 1939 fire season was one of the worst on record for Australia, peaking with Victoria's devastating [[Black Friday bushfires]] of 13 January, but enduring for the full summer, with fires burning the urban fringes of Sydney, Melbourne and Canberra, and ash falling as far away as New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6146527/hg-wells-and-the-big-chill-in-canberras-1939-heatwave/ |title=H.G Wells and the big chill in Canberra's 1939 heatwave|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=20 January 2014|accessdate= }}</ref> The Black Friday fires were the third deadliest on record, with some 71 people killed and 650 houses destroyed.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/> They followed years of drought and a series of extreme heatwaves that were accompanied by strong northerly winds, after a very dry six months. Melbourne hit {{convert|45.6|C|F}} and Adelaide {{convert|46.1|C|F}}. In NSW, Bourke suffered 37 consecutive days above 38 degrees and Menindee hit a record {{convert|49.7|C|F}} on 10 January.<ref name=\"lessons\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/environment/climate-change/lessons-learnt-and-perhaps-forgotten-from-australia-s-worst-fires-20190108-p50qol.html |title=Lessons learnt (and perhaps forgotten) from Australia's 'worst fires'|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=11 January 2019|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nNew South Wales also lost hundreds of houses, thousands of stock and poultry, and thousands of hectares of grazing land.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush Fires Over Wide Area|work=The Argus|date=16 January 1939|page=}}</ref>  By 16 January, disastrous fires were burning in Victoria, New South Wales and the ACT at the climax of a terrible heatwave. Sydney was ringed to the north, south and west by fires from Palm Beach and Port Hacking to the Blue Mountains. Fires blazing at Castle Hill, Sylvania, Cronulla and French's Forest in the city.<ref name=\"lessons\"/><ref name=terrible>{{cite news|title=Terrible Climax to Heatwave|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 January 1939|page=}}</ref> Disastrous fires were also reported at Penrose, Wollongong, Nowra, Bathurst, Ulludulla, Mittagong, Trunkey and Nelligen.<ref name=terrible/> Meanwhile, Canberra faced the \"worst bushfires\" it had experienced, with thousands of hectares burned and a {{convert|45|mi|km|adj=on|order=flip}} fire front driven towards the city by a south westerly gale, destroying pine plantations and many homesteads, and threatening [[Mount Stromlo Observatory]], Government House, and [[Black Mountain (Australian Capital Territory)|Black Mountain]]. Large numbers of men were sent to stand by government buildings in the line of fire.<ref name=terrible/>\n\n; Black Friday\n\nThe state of Victoria was hardest hit, with an area of almost two million hectares burned, 71 people killed, and whole townships wiped out, along with many sawmills and thousands of sheep, cattle and horses around [[Black Friday bushfires|Black Friday]]. Fires had been burning through December, but linked up with devastating force on Friday 13 January, plunging many areas of the state into midday blackness.<ref name=\"RC 1939\">{{cite web|url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-52798639/view?partId=nla.obj-95600830#page/n4/mode/1up|title=Report of the Royal Commission: Introduction - Part 1|publisher=Victorian Government|date=1939|via=Trove, [[National Library of Australia]]|accessdate= }}</ref> The Stretton Royal Commission later wrote wrote:<ref name=\"RC 1939\"/>\n\n{{blockquote|\"On [13 January] it appeared that the whole State was alight. At midday, in many places, it was dark as night. Men carrying hurricane lamps, worked to make safe their families and belongings. Travellers on the highways were trapped by fires or blazing fallen trees, and perished. Throughout the land there was daytime darkness... Steel girders and machinery were twisted by heat as if they had been of fine wire. Sleepers of heavy durable timber, set in the soil, their upper surfaces flush with the ground, were burnt through... Where the fire was most intense the soil was burnt to such a depth that it may be many years before it shall have been restored...\"|Stretton Royal Commission.}}\n\nThe townships of Warrandyte, Yarra Glen, Omeo and Pomonal were badly damaged, and fires burned to the urban fringe of Melbourne, affecting towns including Toolangi, Warburton and Thomson Valley. In the Victorian Alps, the towns of Bright, Cudgewa and Corryong were also hit, along with vast areas in the west, in particular Portland, the Otway Ranges and the Grampians. Black Range, Rubicon, Acheron, Noojee, Tanjil Bren, Hill End, Woods Point, Matlock, Erica, Omeo, Toombullup and the Black Forest were also affected. Huge amounts of smoke and ash were generated, with reports of ash falling as far away as New Zealand.<ref name=FFM/>\n\n; Legacy\n\nAfter the bushfires, Victoria convened a [[Royal Commission]]. Judge Leonard Stretton was instructed to inquire into the causes of the fires, and consider the measures taken to prevent the fires and to protect life and property. He made seven major recommendations to improve forest and fire management, and planned burning became an official fire management practice.<ref name=\"Black Friday 1939\">{{cite web|title=Black Friday 1939|url=https://www.ffm.vic.gov.au/history-and-incidents/black-friday-1939|work=Forest Fire Management Victoria|publisher=\u00a9 State of Victoria (Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning)|accessdate=19 January 2020 |language=en-AU|date=27 February 2017}} [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n\n====1966-7 and Black Tuesday====\n[[File:SmokeStreetsHobart1967.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hobart]] filled with smoke during the [[1967 Tasmanian fires]].]]\n\nIn the summer of 1967, Tasmania suffered its [[1967 Tasmanian fires|most destructive fire season]], and Australia's fourth most deadly on record. A verdant spring had added higher than usual fuel to the state's forest floors, and strong northerly winds and high temperatures drove at least 80 different fires across the south-east, burning to within {{convert|2|km}} of the centre of Hobart, the state capital. The infernos killed 62 people and destroyed almost 1300 homes.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/>\n\n====1993-4 Sydney and NSW eastern seaboard bushfires====\n[[File:Sydney bushfire.jpg|thumb|A pall of bushfire smoke over Sydney during the [[1994 Eastern seaboard fires]].]]\n\nFrom 27 December 1993 to 16 January 1994, [[1994 Eastern seaboard fires|over 800 severe fires]] burned along the coastal areas of New South Wales, affecting the state's most populous regions. Blazes emerged from the Queensland border down the north and central coast, through the Sydney basin and down the south coast to [[Batemans Bay]]. The {{convert|800000|ha|acre|adj=on}} spread of fires were generally contained within less than {{convert|100|km}} from the coast, and many burned through rugged and largely uninhabited country in national parks or nature reserves.<ref name=Cheney>{{cite web|author1=Cheney, N. P.|author2=CSIRO Division of Forestry|url=https://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/6C98BB75496A5AD1CA2569DE00267E48|title=BUSHFIRES - AN INTEGRAL PART OF AUSTRALIA'S ENVIRONMENT|work=The Year Book of Australia 1995|publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics|date=1995|accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref> Dramatic scenes of the city of Sydney shrouded in thick bushfire smoke, and bushland suburbs on fire were broadcast around the world.<ref name=RFS>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/our-districts/mia/photovideo-gallery/2014-photovideo-gallery/twenty-years-on-since-the-1994-fires-seven-news-flashback|title=Twenty years on since the 1994 fires|work=Seven News Flashback|publisher=New South Wales Rural Fire Service|date=6 January 2014|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December, the Dept of Bushfire Services was monitoring more than a dozen fires around the state, and homes were threatened in Turramurra by a fire in the Lane Cove River reserve, and a scrub fire had briefly cut off the holiday village of Bundeena in the [[Royal National Park]], south of Sydney.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bushfire threatens homes in Turramurra|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=29 December 1993|accessdate=|page=}}</ref> ''[[The Age]]'' reported on 7 January that one quarter of NSW was under threat in the worst fires seen in the state for nearly fifty years, as hundreds of firefighters from interstate joined 4000 NSW firefighters battling blazes from Batemans Bay to Grafton. Fires in the Lane Cove River area at Marsfield, Turramurra, West Pymble and Macquarie Park were threatening hundreds of homes, and the fire in the Royal National Park raged toward Bundeena, where rescue boats evacuated 3100 people caught in the path of the fire. With the Prime Minister [[Paul Keating]] on leave, Deputy Prime Minister [[Brian Howe (politician)|Brian Howe]], ordered 100 soldiers to join firefighting efforts, and placed a further 100 on standby.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands flee path of advancing flames|work=The Sunday Age|date=9 January 1994|accessdate=|page=}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January, the Royal National Park fire swept into the southern Sydney suburbs of [[Como West, New South Wales|Como]] and [[Jannali, New South Wales|Jannali]] where many homes would be destroyed, along with two schools a church and a kindergarten.<ref name=\"war diary\">{{cite news|title=War Diary of a State Ablaze|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=15 January 1994|accessdate=|page=}}</ref><ref name=\"leader-20-years-on\">{{cite news|last1=Mutton|first1=Sheree |title=Shire fire horror still lingers 20 years on |url=http://www.theleader.com.au/story/2012100/shire-fire-horror-still-lingers-20-years-on/ |accessdate=22 January 2018 |work=[[St George & Sutherland Shire Leader]]|date=9 January 2014}}</ref> The Como/Jannali fire burnt {{convert|476|ha}} and destroyed 101 houses - more than half of the total homes lost in New South Wales during the January emergency period.<ref name=Cheney/> Also on 8 January, fires had reached to within {{convert|1.5|km}} of Gosford city centre, and some 5000 people had been evacuated over that weekend with homes destroyed at Somersby and Peats Ridge.<ref name=\"war diary\"/>\n\nBy 9 January, more than 16,000 people were on standby for evacuation from the Lower Blue Mountains. Thousands of people were sleeping on the football field at the Central Coast Leagues Club, after the evacuation of Kariong, Woy Woy, Umina, Ettalong and Brisbane Waters. Much of Gosford, Kariong and Somersby had been evacuated, along with Terry Hill. Homes at Menai, Sutherland, Chatswood, Lindfield, Turramurra, Macquarie Park and Sydney's northern beaches had been lost. 60 fires were burning on the north coast, as firefighters battled infernos over {{convert|30|ha}} from Coffs Harbour to the Queensland border. Fires were approaching towns in the Blue Mountains including Blackheath and in the Shoalhaven, including Ulladulla.<ref>{{cite news|title=A round up of all the fire regions|work=The Age|page=2|date=9 January 1994|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n; Legacy\n\nSome 20,000 firefighters were deployed against around 800 fires mainly along the coast and ranges. The fires caused mass evacuations, claimed four lives, destroyed some 225 homes and burnt {{convert|800000|ha|acres}} of bushland. They were met with amongst the largest firefighting efforts in Australian history. A lengthy Coronial inquest followed the fires, leading to the formation of the [[New South Wales Rural Fire Service]].<ref name=RFS/> The ''Rural Fires Act 1997'' was proclaimed on 1 September 1997.<ref name=RFS/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/history|work=NSW Rural Fire Service|title=Our History|date=n.d.|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nBetween 1 November 2019 and 31 January 2020, Australia had one of the worst bush fires in history. The deadliest bushfire disaster was that of \"Black Saturday\" in February 2009 when 180 people died in Victoria. 2019 had been the hottest record year for Australia. Fires have raged near the Australian capital Canberra for weeks, and had shut down the city's airports as flames approached the perimeter. A little more than 24 and a half million acres that have been affected can compare to the 32 million acres of England. Grass fires typically can spread around 14 miles per hour.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50951043|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Australia fires: A visual guide to the bushfire crisis|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Northern Australia ===\nIn the last ten years or so,{{when|date=February 2020}} government licenses have been granted to fire-prevention programs on Aboriginal lands in northern Australia. In this area Aboriginal traditions, which reduce the undergrowth that can fuel bigger blazes, revolve around the monsoon. Land is burned patch by patch using \"cool\" fires in targeted areas during the early dry season, between March and July.<ref name=\"Guardian-Allam-2020-01-18\">{{cite news|author=Allam, Lorena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/19/right-fire-for-right-future-how-cultural-burning-can-protect-australia-from-catastrophic-blazes|title=Right fire for right future: how cultural burning can protect Australia from catastrophic blazes|work=[[Guardian Australia]]|date=18 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> These defensive burning programs began in the 1980s and 1990s when Aboriginal groups moved back onto their native lands. Since this process began, destructive bushfires in northern Australia have burned 57% fewer acres in 2019 than they did on average in the years from 2000 to 2010, the decade before the program started.<ref>{{cite news|author=Fuller, Thomas|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12301169|title=Reducing fire, and cutting carbon emissions, the Aboriginal way|work=[[New York Times]]|via=[[NZ Herald]]|date=17 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOliver Costello from the national Indigenous Firesticks Alliance stated that in southern Australia, Aboriginal knowledge systems of fire management are less valued than in the north. In the [[Kimberley, Western Australia|Kimberley area]], the land council applies local resources and holds community fire planning meetings to ensure the correct people are doing the burning. Burn lines are approved by the group but [[Indigenous ranger]]s set the fires, backed up by modern technology involving constant weather readings and taking into account the conditions of the day. Costello pointed out that northern Australia has developed a collaborative infrastructure for 'cultural burning' and noted that: \"There\u2019s no investment really outside of northern Australia Indigenous fire management of any significance.\"<ref name=\"Guardian-Allam-2020-01-18\"/>\n\n== Factors and causes ==\n=== Ignition ===\nIn recent times most major bush fires have been started in remote areas by dry lightning<ref>{{Cite news|author1=Nguyen, Kevin|author2= Brunero, Tim|author3=Thomas, Sarah|author4=Keane, Daniel|author5=Mills, Nicole|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-11/australias-fires-reveal-arson-not-a-major-cause/11855022|title=The truth about Australia's fires \u2014 arsonists aren't responsible for many this season|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=18 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author1=RMIT ABC Fact Check|author2=Gordon, Josh|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-15/is-arson-mostly-to-blame-for-the-bushfire-crisis/11865724|title=Some Coalition MPS say arson is mostly to blame for the bushfire crisis. Here are the facts|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=14 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> or by electric power lines being brought down or arcing in high winds.  Many fires are as a result of either deliberate arson or carelessness, however these fires normally happen in readily accessible areas and are rapidly brought under control.  Man-made events include [[electric arc|arcing]] from overhead power lines, arson, accidental ignition in the course of agricultural clearing, grinding and welding activities, campfires, cigarettes and dropped matches, sparks from machinery, and [[controlled burn]] escapes. They spread based on the type and quantity of fuel that is available. Fuel can include everything from trees, underbrush and dry grassy fields to homes. Wind supplies the fire with additional oxygen pushing the fire across the land at a faster rate.\n\nLarge, violent wildfires can generate winds of their own, called fire whirls. Fire whirls are like tornadoes and result from the vortices created by the fire's heat. When these vortices are tilted from horizontal to vertical, this creates fire whirls. These whirls have been known to hurl flaming logs and burning debris over considerable distances.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bonsor, Kevin|url=https://science.howstuffworks.com/nature/natural-disasters/wildfire1.htm|title=How Wildfires Work|work=How Stuff Works|date=29 May 2001|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome reports indicate that a changing climate could also be contributing to the ferocity of the 2019\u201320 fires with hotter, drier conditions making the country's fire season longer and much more dangerous.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/climate-and-people/australia-burning-bushfires-bad/|title=Australia is burning \u2013 but why are the bushfires so bad and is climate change to blame?|first=Sarah|last=Newey|date=2 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> Strong winds also promote the rapid spread of fires by lifting burning embers into the air. This is known as spotting and can start a new fire up to {{convert|40|km}} downwind from the fire front.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fire Behaviour|url=https://www.thebushfirefoundation.org/how-fire-behaves/|website=The Bushfire Foundation|date=2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> In the Northern Territory fires can also be spread by black kites, whistling kites and brown falcons. These birds have been spotted picking up burning twigs, flying to areas of unburned grass and dropping them to start new fires there. This exposes their prey attempting to flee the blazes: small mammals, birds, lizards, and insects.<ref name=\"BBC_22Nov2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50511963|title=Australia bushfires: Which animals typically fare best and worst?|work=[[BBC News]]|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nMonths of severe drought and record-breaking temperatures have fueled a series of massive bush fires across Australia. Hot and windy conditions had authorities of Australian Capital Territory declare a state of emergency.\n\n[[File:Fire activity swifts creek 2007 edit.jpg|thumb|800px|center|Looking towards [[Dargo, Victoria]] from [[Swifts Creek, Victoria|Swifts Creek]], 11 January 2006]]\n\n===Topography===\n[[File:Prospect Hill bushfires.jpg|thumb|220px|A hilly bushfire that charred [[Prospect Hill (New South Wales)|Prospect Hill]], in [[Sydney]].]]\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\nBushfires in Australia are generally described as uncontrolled, non-structural fires burning in a grass, [[Shrubland|scrub]], bush, or forested area. The nature of the fire depends somewhat on local [[topography]]. Hilly/mountainous fires burn in areas which are usually densely forested. The land is less accessible and not conducive to agriculture, thus many of these densely forested areas have been saved from [[deforestation]] and are protected by national, state and other parks. The steep terrain increases the speed and intensity of a firestorm. Where settlements are located in hilly or mountainous areas, bushfires can pose a threat to both life and property. Flat/grassland fires burn along flat plains or areas of small undulation, predominantly covered in grasses or scrubland. These fires can move quickly, fanned by high winds in flat topography, and they quickly consume the small amounts of fuel/vegetation available. These fires pose less of a threat to settlements as they rarely reach the same intensity seen in major firestorms as the land is flat, the fires are easier to map and predict, and the terrain is more accessible for [[firefighting]] personnel. Many regions of predominantly flat terrain in Australia have been almost completely deforested for agriculture, reducing the fuel loads which would otherwise facilitate fires in these areas.\n\n=== Climate change ===\n{{See also| Climate change in Australia}}\nAustralia's climate has warmed by more than one degree Celsius over the past century, causing an increase in the frequency and intensity of heatwaves and droughts.<ref name=\"ScientificAmerican\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/australias-angry-summer-this-is-what-climate-change-looks-like/|title=Australia's Angry Summer: This Is What Climate Change Looks Like|author=Abram, Nerilie|author-link=Nerilie Abram|date=31 December 2019|work=Scientific American|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> Eight of Australia's ten warmest years on record have occurred since 2005.<ref name=stuff>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/climate-news/118568474/australia-bushfires-spew-twothirds-of-national-carbon-emissions-in-one-season|title=Australia bushfires spew two-thirds of national carbon emissions in one season|work=Stuff|location=New Zealand|date=3 January 2019|accessdate=}}</ref> A study in 2018 conducted at Melbourne University found that the major droughts of the late 20th century and early 21st century in southern Australia are \"likely without precedent over the past 400 years\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Freund, Mandy|author2=Henley, Ben|author3=Allen, Kathryn|author4=Baker, Patrick|url=https://theconversation.com/recent-australian-droughts-may-be-the-worst-in-800-years-94292|title=Recent Australian droughts may be the worst in 800 years|work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|author= |date=2 May 2018|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Across the country, the average summer temperatures have increased leading to record-breaking hot weather,<ref name=\"auto\"/> with the early summer of 2019 the hottest on record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tai.org.au/sites/default/files/Climate%20of%20the%20Nation%202019%20%5BWEB%5D.pdf|title=Climate of the Nation|year=2019|publisher=The Australia Institute|page=3|issn=|accessdate=}}</ref> 2019 was also Australia's driest ever year since 1900 with rainfall 40% lower than average.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|author=Readfearn, Graham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/jan/13/explainer-what-are-the-underlying-causes-of-australias-shocking-bushfire-season|title=Explainer: what are the underlying causes of Australia's shocking bushfire season?|work=Guardian Australia|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHeatwaves and droughts dry out the undergrowth and create conditions that increase the risk of bushfires. This has become worse in the last 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.climateinstitute.org.au/verve/_resources/bushfirenationalbrief.pdf|title=Bushfire weather in Southeast Australia: Media Brief|work=The Climate Institute|date=26 September 2007|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> Since the mid-1990s, southeast Australia has experienced a 15% decline in late autumn and early winter rainfall and a 25% decline in average rainfall in April and May. Rainfall for January to August 2019 was the lowest on record in the Southern Downs (Queensland) and Northern Tablelands (New South Wales) with some areas 77% below the long term average.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/not-normal-climate-change-bushfire-web/ |title=The Facts about Bushfires and Climate Change|publisher=Climate Council|location=Australia|date=13 November 2019|accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) concluded that ongoing anthropogenic climate change was virtually certain to increase in intensity and frequency of fires in Australia \u2013 a conclusion that has been endorsed in numerous reports since.<ref name=ScientificAmerican/> In November 2019, the Australian Climate Council published a report titled ''This is Not Normal''<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/resources/bushfire-briefing-paper/|title=This is Not Normal: Climate Change and Escalating bushfire risk|last=Colton|first=Schroeder|date=12 November 2019|website=|publisher=Climate Council|location=Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> which also found the catastrophic bushfire conditions affecting NSW and Queensland in late 2019 have been aggravated by climate change.<ref name=\"auto\"/> According to [[Nerilie Abram]] writing in ''[[Scientific American]]'' \"the link between the current extremes and anthropogenic climate change is scientifically indisputable\".<ref name=ScientificAmerican/> In 2020, an international team of scientists found the hot and dry conditions that helped drive Australia\u2019s 2019-2020 bushfire crisis would be eight times more likely to happen if the earth warms by 2C.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/05/bushfire-crisis-conditions-eight-times-more-likely-under-2c-warming-analysis-shows Bushfire crisis conditions eight times more likely under 2C warming, analysis shows], The Guardian, 4 March 2020</ref>\n\n=== Carbon emissions ===\n{{Main|Greenhouse gas emissions by Australia}}\nUntil the [[2019\u20132020 Australian bushfire season]], the forests in Australia were thought to reabsorb all the carbon released in bushfires across the country. This would mean the forests achieved net-zero emissions. However, scientists now say that global warming is making bushfires burn more intensely and frequently and believe the 2019-2020 fires have already released approximately {{convert|350|e6t|e6ST|abbr=off}} of carbon dioxide \u2013 as much as two-thirds of Australia's average annual carbon dioxide emissions ({{convert|530|e6t|e6ST|abbr=off}} in 2017)<ref>{{cite book|title=National Inventory by Economic Sector 2017|work=Australia\u2019s National Greenhouse Accounts|publisher=[[Department of the Environment and Energy]]|date=August 2019|page=3|url=|isbn=|accessdate=}}</ref> in just the past three months. David Bowman, professor of [[pyrogeography]] and fire science at the University of Tasmania warned that so much damage has been done that Australian forests may take more than 100 years to re-absorb the carbon that has been released so far this fire season.<ref name=stuff/>\n\nIn January 2020, the [[Met Office|British Met Office]] said Australia's bushfires in 2019-2020 were expected to contribute 2% to the increase in the atmospheric concentration of major greenhouse gases which are forecast to hit 417 parts per million, one of the largest annual increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide on record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/24/australian-bushfires-to-contribute-to-huge-annual-increase-in-global-carbon-dioxide|title=Australian bushfires to contribute to huge annual increase in global carbon dioxide|work=Guardian Australia|date=24 January 2020|accessdate= }}</ref> Climate studies show that conditions which promote extreme bushfires in Australia will only get worse as more greenhouse gases are added to the atmosphere.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nThe smoke from the fire has created a major pollution hazard, dropping air quality to rating the third worst of all major global cities, according to Swiss-based group AirVisual. Plumes of black carbon have traveled more than 7,000 miles from the fires. Black carbon is harmful to human health and contributes to climate change. \n\n=== Seasonality ===\nBushfires in Australia can occur all year-round, though the severity and the \"bushfire season\" varies by region.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Luke R. H.|author2=McArthur, A. G.|year=1978|title=Bushfires in Australia|publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service|location=Canberra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gQhbkWRlPIW1pumwsHDkWeia8l_QD968SJR80|title=Hot and dry Australia sees wildfire danger rise|last=Sullivan|first=Rohan|date=11 February 2009|publisher=The Association Press|access-date=13 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://burarra.questacon.edu.au/pages/seasons.html | title=Monsoonal Climate | accessdate=9 September 2006 | publisher=Questacon | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320141721/http://burarra.questacon.edu.au/pages/seasons.html | archive-date=20 March 2012 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere is no formal definition for a single bushfire season across the whole of Australia.  There is no one terminology used for periods of fire activity.  The technical terms used for periods of fire risk and fire activity include fire weather season,<ref name=\"bom2020\"/> fire danger season,<ref name=\"bom2020\"/><ref name=\"sacfs2020\"/> bush fire danger period,<ref name=\"nswrfs2020a\"/> fire danger period,<ref name=\"viccfa2020\"/><ref name=\"ntg2020b\"/> fire permit period,<ref name=\"tassfc2020\"/> restricted burning times, and, prohibited burning times,<ref name=\"wabfa1954\"/> and fire season.<ref name=\"ntg2020a\"/>\n\nThe term \"Australian bushfire season\", is a {{linktext|colloquialism}} broadly defined by common usage, from when the first uncontrolled fires start any time from June onwards,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Lucas, Chris|author2=Harris, Sarah|url=https://theconversation.com/its-only-october-so-whats-with-all-these-bushfires-new-research-explains-it-124091|title=It\u2019s only October, so what\u2019s with all these bushfires? New research explains it|work=[[The Conversation]]|date=10 October 2019|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> typically shortened to \"bushfire season\", and applies mainly to southern and eastern Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/7.30/early-start-to-bushfire-season-in-nsw-catches-many/11494054|title=Early start to bushfire season in NSW catches many by surprise|work=7:30|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=9 September 2019|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-12-04/gippsland-warned-of-long-bushfire-season/11755562|title=Bushfire season starts early with Gippsland residents urged to prepare after deadly 'practice run'|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=4 December 2019|author=Maunder, Sarah|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.northerndailyleader.com.au/story/6269553/warmer-temperatures-mean-bushfire-season-could-come-early-again/|title=Bushfire season could hit Australia early following warmer temperatures|work=Northern Daily Leader|date=12 July 2019|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> It can continue through to April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/our-districts/cudgegong/latest-news/bush-fire-danger-period-extended-until-30-april-2019|title=Bush Fire Danger Period Extended until 30 April 2019|publisher=NSW Rural Fire Service|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> Central and northern Australia have two separately defined fire seasons.<ref name=\"ntg2020a\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/rural/2013-10-31/average-fire-season-for-central-australia/5060802?site=alicesprings|title=Central Australia set for 'average' fire season\n|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=31 October 2013|author=Brown, Carmen|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> The colloqial term is typically used in conjunction with the technical terms when conveying information to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southernhighlandnews.com.au/story/6329695/bushfire-season-starts-early/|title=Bushfire season starts early|work=Southern Highland News|date=15 August 2019|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hawkesbury.nsw.gov.au/media/forms/open-burning|title=Open Burning|publisher=Hawkesbury City Council|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian [[Bureau of Meteorology]] defines five \"fire danger seasons\", being times of peak bushfire activity, roughly corresponding to broad bands of latitude across the Australian continent<ref name=\"bom2020\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/weather-services/fire-weather-centre/bushfire-weather/index.shtml|title=Bushfire weather|publisher=Bureau of Meteorology, Australia|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> including winter and spring, across the most northern parts of Australia; spring; spring and summer; summer; and summer and autumn, across the most southern parts of Australia.\n\nEach Australian state and territory jurisdiction defines periods of peak fire risk or fire activity differently. [[New South Wales]] has a default statutory \"bush fire danger period\" defined in law, from 1 October to 31 March.<ref name=\"nswrfs2020a\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/BFDP|title=Bush Fire Danger Period and Fire Permits|publisher=NSW Rural Fire Service|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The state government can then declare different start and end dates for bush fire danger periods for each local government area within the state. In 2019 these started 1 August.<ref name=\"nswrfs2019b\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/news-and-media/media-releases/nsw-rfs-declares-start-of-bush-fire-danger-period|title=NSW RFS declares start of Bush Fire Danger Period|publisher=NSW Rural Fore Service|date=1 August 2019|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] declares a \"fire danger period\" for each local government area. Victorian fire danger periods typically start in October and finish as late as May.<ref name=\"viccfa2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/warnings-restrictions/restrictions-during-the-fire-danger-period|title=Restrictions During the Fire Danger Period|publisher=Country Fire Association|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The [[Government of South Australia|South Australia Government]] declares a \"fire danger season\" for each local government area, potentially starting in October and finishing at the end of April.<ref name=\"sacfs2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfs.sa.gov.au/site/bans_and_ratings/fire_danger_season_dates.jsp|title=Fire Danger Season Dates|publisher=South Australian Country Fire Service|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The [[Government of Tasmania|Tasmanian Government]] declares \"fire permit period\"s for local government areas. In 2019 this commenced 31 October.<ref name=\"tassfc2020\">{{cite web|url=https://messages.fire.tas.gov.au/sites/default/files/filefield_paths/-TFS%20Fire%20Permit%20Period%20Declaration.pdf|title=Fire Permit Period Declaration|publisher=State Fire Commission, Tasmania|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> [[Western Australia]] requires each local government area to declare its own \"restricted burning times\" roughly aligned with spring and autumn, and \"prohibited burning times\" roughly aligned with summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waroona.wa.gov.au/services/emergency-services/fire-control-information.aspx|title=Fire Control Information 2019/20|publisher=Waroona Shire Council|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.donnybrook-balingup.wa.gov.au/services/fire-emergency-management.aspx|title=Fire|publisher=Donnybrook Belingup Shire|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wabfa1954\">{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.wa.gov.au/legislation/prod/filestore.nsf/FileURL/mrdoc_41660.htm/$FILE/Bush%20Fires%20Act%201954%20-%20%5B09-h0-01%5D.html?OpenElement|title=Bush Fires Act 1954 - Western Australia|publisher=Government of Western Australia|date=1954|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The [[Northern Territory]] defines two broad \"fire seasons\", a northern fire season, which can run from April to November, and a central Australian fire season, which can run from October to March.<ref name=\"ntg2020a\">{{cite web|url=https://securent.nt.gov.au/prepare-for-an-emergency/bushfires/fire-management-in-the-nt|title=Fire management in the NT|publisher=Northern Territory Government|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The Government also refers to these as \"fire danger periods\".<ref name=\"ntg2020b\">{{cite web|url=https://denr.nt.gov.au/news/2019/central-australian-fire-season-commencement|title=Central Australian fire season commencement|date=4 December 2019|publisher=Northern Territory Government|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nBushfire seasons are commonly grouped into years such as \"[[2019\u20132020 Australian bushfire season]]\" and typically apply to the season for southern and eastern Australia; from 1 June to 31 May annually.\n\n== Impact on wildlife ==\nBush fires kill animals directly and also destroy local habitats, leaving the survivors vulnerable even once the fires have passed.  Professor Chris Dickman at Sydney University estimates that in the first three months of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|2019\u20132020 bushfires]], over 800&nbsp;million animals died in NSW, and more than one billion nationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sydney.edu.au/news-opinion/news/2020/01/08/australian-bushfires-more-than-one-billion-animals-impacted.html|title=More than one billion animals killed in Australian bushfires|publisher=University of Sydney|date=8 January 2020|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> This figure includes mammals, birds, and reptiles but does not include insects, bats or frogs. Many of these animals were burnt to death in the fires, with many others dying later due to the depletion of food and shelter resources and predation by feral cats and red foxes. Dickman adds that Australia has the highest rate of species loss of any area in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sydney.edu.au/news-opinion/news/2020/01/03/a-statement-about-the-480-million-animals-killed-in-nsw-bushfire.html|title=A statement about the 480 million animals killed in NSW bushfires since September|publisher=University of Sydney|date=3 January 2020|accessdate=}}</ref> with fears that some of Australia's native species, like the Kangaroo Island dunnart, may even become extinct because of the current fires.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/the-weekend/audio/2018729608/kiwi-volunteers-helping-fire-affected-australian-animals|title=Kiwi volunteers helping fire-affected Australian animals|work=RNZ|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n[[Koala]]s are perhaps the most vulnerable because they are slow-moving. In extreme fires, koalas tend to climb up to the top of a tree and curl into a ball where they become trapped. In January 2020 it was reported that half of the 50,000 koalas on [[Kangaroo Island]] off Australia's southern coast, which are kept separate to those on the mainland as insurance for the species\u2019 future, are thought to have died in the previous few weeks.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/06/kangaroo-koala-australia-bushfires-wildfires-die|title=The world loves kangaroos and koalas. Now we are watching them die in droves|work=Guardian Australia|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nWildlife ecologist Professor Euan Ritchie from Deakin University says that when fires have passed, frogs and [[skink]]s are left vulnerable when their habitats have been destroyed. Loss of habitat also affects already endangered species such as the western ground parrot, the Leadbeater's possum, the Mallee emu-wren (a bird which cannot fly very far), and Gilbert's potoroo. Beekeepers have also lost hives in bushfires.<ref name=\"BBC_22Nov2019\"/>\n\nKangaroos and wallabies can move quickly trying to escape from fires. However, the Guardian reported in January 2020 that dozens, maybe hundreds of kangaroos \"perished in their droves\" as they tried to outrun the flames near Batlow in NSW.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The most resilient animals are those that can burrow or fly. Possums often get singed, but can sometimes hide in tree hollows. Wombats and snakes tend to go underground.<ref name=BBC_22Nov2019/>\n\n[[Goanna]]s can benefit from bushfires. Dickman says: \"In central Australia, we've seen goannas coming out from their burrows after a fire and picking off injured animals \u2013 singed birds, young birds, small mammals, surface-dwelling lizards, and snakes.\"<ref name=BBC_22Nov2019/>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nIn South Australia, Kangaroo Island was devastated when 25,000 Koalas were killed. The island is renowned for its mixture of animal species, and fear that it may never recover its population. Tens of thousands of farm animals, mostly sheep, were also killed in the fire on Kangaroo Island. There are concerns about the survival of endangered species on Kangaroo Island, which include the dunnart (a mouse-like marsupial) and the black glossy cockatoo.\n\n== Impact on humans ==\n\nThe most devastating impact on humans is that bushfires have killed over 800 people since 1851.<ref name=Tronson/> In addition to loss of life, homes, properties, and livestock are destroyed potentially leaving people homeless, traumatised, and without access to electricity, telecommunications and, in some cases, to drinking water.<ref name=\"reuters.com\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-australia-bushfires-insurance/australia-strengthens-bushfire-defenses-as-economic-environmental-costs-mount-idUSKBN1Z601F Australia strengthens bushfire defenses as economic, environmental costs mount], Reuters, 7 January 2020</ref>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nAt least 33 people have been killed, 4 of which were firefighters. About 2,000 homes have been destroyed, which has forced thousands to seek shelter elsewhere. Two people have also died on Kangaroo Island in South Australia. More than 80 homes were destroyed in South Australia near Adelaide Hills, as well as one-third of the vineyards that provide grapes for the wine industry.\n\n=== Health ===\nBushfires produce particulate-matter pollution \u2013 airborne particles that are small enough to enter and damage human lung tissue. Following the [[Hazelwood Power Station#Coal mine fire|Hazelwood fire]] in 2014, Fay Johnston, an associate professor of public health at the University of Tasmania's Menzies Institute for Medical Research, says young children exposed to smoke either as infants, toddlers or in the womb develop changes to their lung function. She says: \"Unborn babies exposed to the Hazelwood smoke were more likely to experience coughs or colds two to four years after the fires.\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\">{{cite news|author=McCauley, Dana|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/health-impacts-of-bushfires-won-t-be-known-for-years-experts-say-20200106-p53p87.html|title=Health impacts of bushfires won't be known for years, experts say|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Other studies conducted in Australia show an increase in respiratory diseases among adults stemming from air pollution caused by bushfires.<ref>{{cite news|author=Salinger, Jim|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/08/australia-bushfires-aotearoa-new-zealand-has-become-kikorangi-mawhero-land-of-the-long-pink-cloud|title=Australia's bushfires mean New Zealand has become the land of the long pink cloud|work=Guardian Australia|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of intense smoke and air pollution stemming from the fires, in January 2020 Canberra measured the worst air quality index of any major city in the world. The orange-tinged smoke entered homes and offices buildings across the capital making breathing outside very difficult, forcing businesses and institutions to shut their doors.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Lansdown, Sarah|author2=Whyte, Sally|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6566337/canberra-shuts-down-as-smoke-smothers-city/?cs=14225|title=Canberra shuts down as smoke smothers city|work=The Canberra Times|date=5 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Studies show that residents of highly polluted cities also have an increased risk of heart attack, stroke, and diabetes. Professor Jalaluddin, a chief investigator with the Centre for Air Pollution, Energy and Health Policy Research, says: \"There is increasing evidence around air pollution and (the development of) neurological conditions, for example, Parkinson's disease and Alzheimer's.\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\"/>\n\nProf David Bowman, director of the Fire Centre Research Hub at the [[University of Tasmania]], referred to the [[2019-2020 Australian bushfire season|2019\u20132020 fires]] as \"absolutely transformative and unprecedented\" in scale and stated, \"It's pretty much a third of the Australian population that has been impacted, with prolonged, episodic exposure and sometimes extreme health impacts.\" Since September 2019, close to 3,000 firefighters have been out every day in NSW battling blazes. The NSW RFS stated that close to 90% of those are unpaid volunteers.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mao, Frances|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50887982|title=Australia fires: The thousands of volunteers fighting the flames|work=BBC News|date=24 December 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> David McBride, associate professor of occupational and environmental medicine at the [[University of Otago]] stated, \"They push themselves to the limit \u2013 they can suffer heat stress, which is a life-threatening injury, and end up with chronic bronchitis and asthma\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Fyfe, James|author2=Wilton, James|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2020/01/australia-bushfires-concern-over-long-term-effects-on-firefighters-health.html|title=Australia bushfires: Concern over long-term effects on firefighters' health|work=NewsHub|location=New Zealand|date=10 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Psychological problems ===\nPsychological problems following a major bushfire appear to develop when people have a chance to stop and reflect on their experience. A study of 1,526 people who experienced significant losses in the 1983 Ash Wednesday bushfires found that after 12 months, 42% met the criteria for a psychiatric problem which is double the prevalence in an unaffected community. After twenty months this figure had dropped to 23%.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://oem.bmj.com/content/59/4/215|title=Bushfires: are we doing enough to reduce the human impact?|journal=Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine|volume=59|number=4|author=Sim, M.|date=April 2002|accessdate=13 February 2020|doi=10.1136/oem.59.4.215}}</ref>\n\nA typical example of how people are affected is described by the 2016 fire at [[Yarloop]] in Western Australia. It virtually destroyed the town (population 395) including 180 homes, historic timber workshops, factories, an old church, the old hospital, shops, the hotel, the fire station and a part of the school. Two people died. Damage to infrastructure included the Samson Brook Bridge, Salmon River Bridge and power infrastructure supplying thousands of homes in the area.<ref>{{cite news|author=Young, Emma|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/national/western-australia/emergency-fire-warning-for-waroona-and-preston-beach-20160107-gm0r5l.html|title=WA fires: deadly Waroona blaze contained but not controlled, downgraded to 'advice'|work=WA Today|date=9 January 2016|accessdate=}}</ref> Two years later, people from Yarloop were still suffering from trauma distress from the fire. Apart from the economic losses suffered by those who lived there, the dislocation to their lives was so great that many in the community were doubtful that the town would be rebuilt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bushfirefront.org.au/home/fire-facts/impacts-of-bushfires/|title=Impacts of Bushfires|work=Bushfire Front|date=2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> The [[Government of Western Australia|WA Government]] subsequently spent {{AUD}}64&nbsp;million rebuilding the town and the surrounding communities.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Birch, Laura|author2=Lynch, Jacqueline|author3=Ferguson, Holly|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-22/yarloop-rebuilding-after-devastating-bushfires/11730556|title=Rising from the ashes, Yarloop bounces back after devastating bushfires in 2016|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic impact ===\nEconomic damage from 2009's Black Saturday fires, the costliest in Australia's history, reached an estimated {{AUD}}4.4&nbsp;billion. Moody's Analytics says the cost of the 2019\u20132020 bushfires is likely to exceed even that figure and will cripple consumer confidence and harm industries such as farming and tourism.<ref>{{cite news|author=Butler, Ben|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/08/economic-impact-of-australias-bushfires-set-to-exceed-44bn-cost-of-black-saturday|title=Economic impact of Australia's bushfires set to exceed $4.4bn cost of Black Saturday|work=Guardian Australia|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> Medical bills from the current fires and smoke haze are expected to reach hundreds of millions of dollars with one analysis suggesting disruptions caused by the fire and smoke haze could cost Sydney as much as {{AUD}}50&nbsp;million a day.<ref>{{cite news|author=McDonald, Tim|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-50862349|title=Australia fires: The huge economic cost of Australia's bushfires|work=BBC News|location=United Kingdom|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> The Insurance Council of Australia estimates that claims for damage from the fires would be more than {{AUD}}700&nbsp;million, with claims expected to jump when more fire-hit areas become accessible. In January 2020, it was reported that the [[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group|ANZ]] gauge of consumer confidence fell to its lowest level in more than four years.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/>\n\nIn response to the current fires, the federal government announced that compensation would be paid to volunteer firefighters, military personnel would be deployed to assist, and an {{AUD}}2&nbsp;billion bush fire recovery fund would be established. New South Wales, which has been hardest hit by the crisis, has pledged {{AUD}}1&nbsp;billion focused on repairing infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|author=Heath, Michael|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-08/australian-economy-staggers-under-wildfires-setting-up-stimulus|title=Australian Economy Struck by Wildfires, Setting Up Stimulus|work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg Green]]|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n \nAbout 27.2 million acres of bush, forest, and parks across Australia have burned. New South Wales and Victoria have been the worst hit states. In New South Wales, fire has affected about 12 and a half million acres. In Victoria, almost 3 million acres have been burned. \n\n== Official inquiries ==\nAfter many major bushfires, state and federal governments have initiated inquiries to see what could be done to address the problem. A parliamentary report from 2010 stated that between 1939 and 2010, there have been at least 18 major bushfire inquiries including state and federal parliamentary committee inquiries, [[Council of Australian Governments|COAG]] reports, coronial inquiries and Royal Commissions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Former_Committees/agric/completed_inquiries/2008-10/bushfires/report/c02|title=Chapter 2 \u2013 Previous bushfire inquiries|work=The incidence and severity of bushfires across Australia|author=Senate Select Committee on Agricultural and Related Industries|publisher=Parliament of Australia|date=13 August 2010|access-date=15 February 2020|page=|isbn=978-1-74229-349-3}}</ref> Another report published in 2015 stated there have been 51 inquiries into wildfires and wildfire management since 1939. The authors noted that Royal Commissions were not the most effective way to learn from past bushfire events.<ref>{{cite conference |url=https://www.bnhcrc.com.au/file/4881/download?token=PFQPk5fa|title=Learning from Adversity: What has 75 years of bushfire inquiries (1939-2013) taught us?, Report no 2015.019|author1=Eburn, Michael|author1-link=|author2=Hudson, David|author3=Chal, Ignatious|author4=Dovers, Stephen|date=2 September 2014|conference=Research Forum at the Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC & AFAC conference|conference-url= |editor= |others=[[Australian National University]]|volume= |edition= |book-title= |publisher=Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC|archive-url= |archive-date= |location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]]|pages= |format=requires download |id= |isbn= |bibcode= |oclc= |doi= |access-date=15 February 2020|quote=''The fact that catastrophic events continue to recur is evidence either that the community is failing to learn the lessons from the past, or the inquiries fail to identify the true learning \u2013 that catastrophic events may be inevitable, or that Royal Commissions are not the most effective way to identify relevant lessons from past events.''|ref= |postscript= |language=en-AU|page=4 |at= |trans-title= }}</ref> Many of the inquiries into bushfires have recommended \"hazard reduction burning\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Bonyhady, Nick|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/prime-minister-says-hazard-reduction-burns-are-climate-action-20200121-p53tha.html|title=Prime Minister says hazard reduction burns as important as emissions|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> intended to reduce the available fuel and have set targets to burn a certain percentage of forest each year to reduce risk. Planned burns are  difficult to do safely and many of the investigations and Royal Commissions have found these targets are seldom met. At the same time, fire management experts disagree on how effective planned burning is.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mannix, Liam|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/these-scientists-think-we-re-in-a-bushfire-spiral-they-have-a-plan-20200123-p53u68.html|title=These scientists think we're in a 'bushfire spiral'. They have a plan|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, during the 2019\u20132020 bushfire season, Prime Minister Scott Morrison raised the prospect of establishing another royal commission. In an interview on [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC-TV]] ''[[7.30]]'', Morrison stated that any inquiry into the crisis would need to be comprehensive and investigate climate change as well as other possible causes.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Morrison |first=Scott |subject= |subject-link=Scott Morrison |last2= |first2= |subject2= |subject-link2= |last3= |first3= |subject3= |subject-link3= |last4= |first4= |subject4= |subject-link4= |interviewer=[[Michael Rowland (news presenter)|Michael Rowland]] |title=Scott Morrison defends the Government's response to the bushfires |type= |url=https://www.abc.net.au/7.30/scott-morrison-defends-the-governments-response-to/11856618 |format=Streaming video |work=[[7.30]] |publisher=[[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC-TV]]|location= |date=9 January 2020 |year= |page= |pages= |access-date=15 February 2020 |archive-url= |archive-date= |url-status= |quote=''... there will be a time, I think, to ensure that we work with the states and territories to get the proper inquiry in place. It needs to be comprehensive, it needs to deal with contributing factors which is everything from hazard reduction to climate change through to the response issues, the national coordination matters and, of course, resilience and planning for the future.''}}</ref>\n\n== Warnings ==\nDuring the fire season, the [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology (BOM)]] provides fire weather forecasts. Fire agencies determine the appropriate Fire Danger Rating by considering the predicted weather including temperature, relative humidity, wind speed and dryness of vegetation. These Fire Danger Ratings are a feature of weather forecasts and alert the community to the actions they should take in preparation for the day. Ratings are broadcast via newspapers, radio, TV, and the internet.<ref name=\"Country Fire Authority\">{{cite web|date=2020|url=https://cdn.cfa.vic.gov.au/documents/20143/80821/Fire-Danger-Ratings-Brochure-Apr-2017.pdf/b253d413-aa46-600c-e529-e4f9e12fe36f|title=Fire Danger Rating Brochure|agency=[[Country Fire Authority]]|publisher=Government of Victoria|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, a standardised ''Fire Danger Rating'' (FDR) was adopted by all Australian states. This included a whole new level \u2013 catastrophic fire danger. The first time this level of danger was forecast for Sydney was in November 2019 during the 2019\u20132020 bushfire season.<ref>{{cite news|author=Cox, Lisa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/nov/11/catastrophic-fire-danger-what-does-it-mean-and-and-what-should-we-do-in-these-conditions|title=Catastrophic fire danger: what does it mean and what should we do in these conditions?|work=Guardian Australia|date=11 November 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> In 2010, following a national review of the bush fire danger ratings, new trigger points for each rating were introduced for grassland areas in most jurisdictions.\n\n<!--The colours in the following table are based on the Fire Danger Rating at the CFS website, http://www.cfs.sa.gov.au/site/fire_restrictions/fire_bans.jsp -->\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Fire Danger Rating\n|-\n!Category\n!Fire Danger Index\n|-\n|style = \"background:#C80815\" | '''Catastrophic / Code Red'''\n|Forest 100+ Grass 150+\n|-\n|style = \"background:#FF4040\" | '''Extreme'''\n|Forest 75\u2013100 Grass 100\u2013150\n|-\n|style = \"background:orange\" | '''Severe'''\n|Forest 50\u201375 Grass 50\u2013100\n|-\n|style = \"background:#FCF75E\" | '''Very high'''\n|25\u201350\n|-\n|style = \"background:skyblue\" | '''High'''\n|12\u201325\n|-\n|style = \"background:#ADDFAD\" | '''Low to moderate'''\n|0\u201312\n|}\n\n==Remote monitoring==\n[[Wildfire#Detection|Remote monitoring of wildfires]] is done in Australia. Geoscience Australia developed the (real-time) Sentinel bushfire monitoring system. It uses data from satellites to help fire-fighting agencies assess and manage risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-11/real-time-bushfire-monitoring-system-to-be-developed/6688510|title=Real-time bushfire monitoring satellite system to be developed in Australia|date=11 August 2015|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csiro.au/en/Research/Astronomy/Earth-observation/Sentinel-hotspots|title=Bushfire tracking with Sentinel Hotspots|website=www.csiro.au}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sentinel.ga.gov.au/|title=Sentinel Hotspots|website=sentinel.ga.gov.au}}</ref> There is also MyFireWatch, which is a program based on an existing Department of Fire and Emergency Services (DFES) program, redeveloped by Landgate and Edith Cowan University (ECU) for use by the general public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-09-28/myfirewatch-brings-bushfire-information-to-wa-outback/5772860|title=Better bushfire information for regional communities|first=Natasha|last=Harradine|date=28 September 2014|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myfirewatch.landgate.wa.gov.au/|title=MyFireWatch \u2013 Bushfire map information Australia|website=myfirewatch.landgate.wa.gov.au}}</ref>\nBesides the use of satellites, Australian firefighters also make use of [[UAV]]'s as a tool for combating fire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/news/drones-to-assist-firefighters-in-emergencies/|title=Drones to assist firefighters in emergencies|website=NSW Government}}</ref>\n\n== Regional management ==\nThe [[Australasian Fire Authorities Council]] (AFAC) is the peak body responsible for representing fire, emergency services, and land management agencies in the Australasian region.\n\n=== Queensland ===\nThe Rural Fire Service (RFS) is a volunteer-based firefighting agency and operates as part of the [[Queensland Fire and Emergency Services]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruralfire.qld.gov.au/|title=Rural Fire Service Queensland}}</ref>\n\n=== New South Wales ===\n[[Fire and Rescue NSW]] (FRNSW), the Forestry Corporation of NSW (FCNSW), the [[National Parks and Wildlife Service (New South Wales)|National Parks and Wildlife Service]] (NPWS) and the [[New South Wales Rural Fire Service]] (RFS) work together to manage and respond to fires across New South Wales.\n\n=== South Australia ===\nThe [[Country Fire Service]] is a volunteer-based fire service in the state of South Australia. The CFS operates as a part of the [[South Australian Fire and Emergency Services Commission]] (SAFECOM).\n\n=== Victoria ===\n[[File:Major Victorian bushfires in the 2000s.PNG|thumb|right|Major bushfires in Victoria in the 2000s]]\n{{main|Bushfires in Victoria}}\n\nIn Victoria, the [[Country Fire Authority]] (CFA) provides firefighting and other emergency services to country areas and regional townships within the state, as well as large portions of the outer suburban areas and growth corridors of [[Melbourne]] not covered by the [[Metropolitan Fire Brigade (Melbourne)|Metropolitan Fire Brigade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/|title=Country Fire Authority|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nResponsibility for fire suppression and management, including planned burning on public land such as State Forests and National Parks, which makes up about 7.1 million hectares or about one-third of the State, sits with the [[Department of Environment, Land, Water, and Planning|Department of Environment, Land, Water, and Planning (DELWP)]].\n\n=== Western Australia ===\nThe [[Department of Fire and Emergency Services]] (DFES) and the [[Department of Parks and Wildlife (Western Australia)|Department of Parks and Wildlife]] (P&W) have joint responsibility for bushfire management in Western Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfes.wa.gov.au/|title=Welcome to DFES|work= Department of Fire and Emergency Services of Western Australia|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref> DFES is an umbrella organisation supporting the Fire and Rescue Service (FRS), Bush Fire Service (BFS), Volunteer Fire and Rescue Service (VFRS), State Emergency Service (SES), Volunteer Fire and Emergency Service (VFES), Emergency Services Cadets and the Volunteer Marine Rescue Service (VMR).\n\n=== Tasmania ===\nThe [[Tasmania Fire Service]] manages bushfires in Tasmania with the help of [[Tasmanian Parks and Wildlife Service]] and [[Forestry Tasmania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fire.tas.gov.au/Show?pageId=colAbout |publisher=Tasmania Fire Service |title=About TFS |year=2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.dpac.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/208131/1.Tasmanian_Bushfires_Inquiry_Report.pdf |isbn=978-0-9923581-0-5 |title=2013 Tasmanian Bushfires Inquiry: Volume 1}}</ref>\n\n== Guidelines for survival ==\nLocal authorities provide education and information for residents in bushfire-prone regions regarding the location of current fires,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/fires-near-me | title= NSW Current Fires | publisher= NSW Rural Fire Service }}</ref> preservation of life and property<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/2933/BushFireSurvivalPlan.pdf | title=How to survive a bushfire | accessdate=20 February 2017 | publisher= NSW Rural Fire Service }}</ref> and when to escape by car.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.driverknowledgetests.com/resources/how-to-drive-through-a-bushfire/ | title=Driving in a bushfire | accessdate=20 February 2017 | date=13 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Major bushfires in Australia ==\n{{main|List of major bushfires in Australia}}\nBushfires have accounted for over 800 deaths in Australia since 1851 and, in 2012, the total accumulated cost was estimated at $1.6&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://romseyaustralia.com/firesum.html|title=Summary of Major Bush Fires in Australia Since 1851|accessdate=29 October 2010|work=Romsey Australia}}</ref> In terms of monetary cost however, they rate behind the damage caused by drought, [[storm|severe storms]], [[hail]], and [[cyclone]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ema.gov.au/ema/emadisasters.nsf/webEventsByCategory?OpenView&Start=1&Count=30&Expand=1#1|title=EMA Disasters Database|work=Emergency management Australia|accessdate=30 October 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20101118000000/http://www.ema.gov.au/ema/emadisasters.nsf/webEventsByCategory?OpenView&Start=1&Count=30&Expand=1#1|archive-date=18 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> perhaps because they most commonly occur outside highly populated urban areas.  However, the severe fires of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|summer of 2019\u20132020]] affected densely populated areas including holiday destinations leading NSW Rural Fire Services Commissioner, Shane Fitzsimmons, to claim it was \"absolutely\" the worst bushfire season on record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/extraordinary-2019-ends-with-deadliest-day-of-the-worst-fire-season-20191231-p53nw0.html|title='Extraordinary' 2019 ends with deadliest day of the worst fire season|author1=Alexander, Harriet|author2=Chung, Laura|author3=Chrysanthos, Natassia|author4=Drevikovsky, Janek|author5=Brickwood, James|date=1 January 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Australia}}\n* [[Aerial firefighting and forestry in southern Australia]]\n* [[AS3959]]\n* [[List of Australian bushfire seasons]]\n* [[List of major bushfires in Australia]]\n* [[List of natural disasters in Australia]]\n* [[McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index]]\n* [[Pyrotron]], a device designed to help firefighters better understand how to combat the rapid spread of bush fires\n* [[Wildfires in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<ref>\u201cAustralia Fires: A Visual Guide to the Bushfire Crisis.\u201d BBC News, BBC, 31 January 2020, www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50951043.\n</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.bom.gov.au/weather-services/fire-weather-centre/bushfire-weather/index.shtml Bureau of Meteorology]\n\n{{Wildland Firefighting}}\n{{Bushfires in Australia}}\n{{Australian Fire Services}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bushfires In Australia}}\n[[Category:Bushfires in Australia| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Bushfire|general information on uncontrolled fires in non-urban areas|Wildfire}}\n{{short description|Frequently occurring wildfire events}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:Swifts creek 14-12-2006 1600 -2.jpg|thumb|right|Looking towards the town [[Swifts Creek, Victoria]], in December 2006 during the [[2006-07 Australian bushfire season|Victorian Alpine fires]]]]\n[[File:2003 Bushfires aftermath, Big River near Anglers Rest.jpg|right|thumb|Intense bushfires can seriously impact the environment, such as here by the [[Big River (Victoria)|Big River]], near [[Anglers Rest, Victoria|Anglers Rest]], [[East Gippsland]], after the [[2003 Eastern Victorian alpine bushfires|2003 Victorian fires]]]]\n\n'''Bushfires in Australia''' are a widespread and regular occurrence that have contributed significantly to shaping the nature of the continent over millions of years. Eastern Australia is one of the most fire-prone regions of the world, and its predominant eucalyptus forests have evolved to thrive on the phenomenon of bushfire.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Making Of The Bush: a portrait of the island continent |episode-link= |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7299705?selectedversion=NBD9997404 |access-date=12 February 2020 |series=Nature of Australia |series-link= |first=John |last=Vandenbeld |network=[[ABC TV (Australia)|ABC TV]] |station= |date=1988 |season= |series-no= |number=3 |minutes=55 |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=en-AU}}</ref> However the fires can cause significant property damage and loss of both human and animal life. Bushfires have killed approximately 800 people in Australia since 1851,<ref name=Tronson>{{cite web |last1=Tronson |first1=Mark |title=Bushfires \u2013 across the nation |url=https://www.christiantoday.co.nz/news/bushfires-across-the-nation.html |website=Christian Today|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> and [[1,000,000,000|billions]] of animals.\n\nThe most destructive fires are usually preceded by extreme high temperatures, low relative humidity and strong winds, which combine to create ideal conditions for the rapid spread of fire.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\">{{cite news|author=Williams, Liz T.|url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/science-environment/2011/11/the-worst-bushfires-in-australias-history/|title=The worst bushfires in Australia\u2019s history|date=3 November 2011|work=[[Australian Geographic]]|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Severe fire storms are often named according to the day on which they peaked, including the five most deadly blazes: [[Black Saturday bushfires|Black Saturday]] 2009 in Victoria (173 people killed, 2000 homes lost); [[Ash Wednesday bushfires|Ash Wednesday]] 1983 in Victoria and South Australia (75 dead, nearly 1900 homes); [[Black Friday bushfires|Black Friday]] 1939 in Victoria (71 dead, 650 houses destroyed), [[1967 Tasmanian fires|Black Tuesday]] 1967 in Tasmania (62 people and almost 1300 homes); and the [[1925-26 Victorian bushfire season|Gippsland fires and Black Sunday]] of 1926 in Victoria (60 people killed over a two-month period).<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/> Other major [[conflagration]]s include the 1851 [[Black Thursday bushfires]], the [[2006\u201307 Australian bushfire season|2006 December bushfires]], the [[1974-75 Australian bushfire season|1974-75 fires]] that affected 15% of Australia,<ref>{{cite web|title=New South Wales, December 1974 Bushfire - New South Wales|url=https://knowledge.aidr.org.au/resources/bushfire-new-south-wales-1974/|website=Australian Institute for Disaster Resilience|publisher=Government of Australia|accessdate=13 January 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113201506/https://knowledge.aidr.org.au/resources/bushfire-new-south-wales-1974/|archivedate=13 January 2020|quote=During the summer between 1974 and 1975, Australia experienced its worst bushfire season in 30 years. Approximately 15 per cent of Australia's physical land mass sustained extensive fire damage. This equates to roughly around 117 million ha.}}</ref> and the ongoing [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|2019\u201320 bushfires]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/extraordinary-2019-ends-with-deadliest-day-of-the-worst-fire-season-20191231-p53nw0.html|title='Extraordinary' 2019 ends with deadliest day of the worst fire season|date=31 December 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en-AU|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, it was estimated that over 1.25&nbsp;billion animals have died in the [[2019-2020 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/estimated-125-billion-animals-killed-australian-bushfires-2020-jan|title=Estimated 1.25 billion animals killed in Australian bushfires|work=TV10|date=10 January 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe gradual drying of the Australian continent over the last 15 million years has produced an ecology and environment prone to fire, which has resulted in many specialised adaptations amongst [[Flora of Australia|flora]] and [[Fauna of Australia|fauna]]. Some of the country's flora has evolved to rely on bushfires for reproduction. [[Aboriginal Australian]]s used to [[Fire-stick farming|use fire]] to clear grasslands for hunting and to clear tracks through dense vegetation,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The history of fire in Australia \u2014 and how it can help us face the bushfires of the future |episode-link= |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-10/fires-bushfires-in-australia-history-lessons-for-future/11937652 |series=Rear Vision |series-link= |author1=Ross, Monique |author2=Quince, Annabelle |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |station= |date=11 January 2020 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=en-AU |access-date=13 February 2020 }}</ref> and European settlers have also had to adapt to using fire to enhance agriculture and forest management since the 19th century. Fire and forest management has evolved again through the 20th and 21st centuries with the spread of national parks and nature reserves, while human-caused [[global warming]] is predicted to continue increasing the frequency of blazes.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== History ==\n{{See|Eucalyptus#Fire hazard}}\n[[File:Epicormic Shoots from an Epicormic Bud on Eucalyptus following Bushfire 2, near Anglers Rest, Vic, Aust, jjron 27.3.2005.jpg|left|thumb|[[Epicormic shoots]] sprouting vigorously from epicormic buds beneath the thick bushfire damaged [[Bark (botany)|bark]] of a ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' tree \u2013 one of the mechanisms evolved by plants to survive bushfires]]\n[[File:Bushfire damage.jpg|thumb|right|Bushfire damage to forests in [[East Gippsland]], Victoria from the [[2003 Eastern Victorian alpine bushfires]], two years after fires swept through the area, showing the recovery of trees and undergrowth]]\n\n===Before European settlement===\n\nAccording to [[Tim Flannery]] (''[[The Future Eaters]]''), fire is one of the most important forces at work in the Australian environment. Some plants have [[evolution|evolved]] a variety of mechanisms to survive or even require bushfires (possessing [[epicormic shoot]]s or [[lignotuber]]s that sprout after a fire, or developing fire-resistant or fire-triggered [[seed]]s), or even encourage fire ([[eucalypt]]s contain flammable oils in the leaves) as a way to eliminate competition from less fire-tolerant species.<ref>{{cite book|author=White, M. E.|year=1986|title=The Greening of Gondwana|publisher=Reed Books|location=Frenchs Forest, Australia|isbn=|page=}}</ref> Early European explorers of the Australian coastline noted extensive bushfire smoke. [[Abel Janszoon Tasman]]'s expedition saw smoke drifting over the coast of Tasmania in 1642 and noted blackened trunks and baked earth in the forests. While charting the east coast in 1770, Captain Cook's crew saw autumn fires in the bush burning on most days of the voyage.<ref name=Blainey>{{cite book|author=Blainey, Geoffrey|author-link=Geoffrey Blainey|title=The Rise and Fall of Ancient Australia|publisher=Penguin Viking|location=|isbn=|publication-date=2015}}</ref>{{rp|50\u201351}}\n\nThe fires would have been caused by both natural phenomenon and human hands. Aborigines in many regions set fire to grasslands in the hope of producing lusher grass to fatten kangaroos and other game and, at certain times of year, burned fire breaks as a precaution against bushfire.<ref name=Blainey/>{{rp|59}} [[Fire-stick farming]] was also used to facilitate hunting and to promote the growth of bush potatoes and other edible ground-level plants.  In central Australia, they used fire in this way to manage their country for thousands of years.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227223739/http://www.schools.nt.edu.au/tlcland/publications/Fire%20Book.pdf|url=http://www.schools.nt.edu.au/tlcland/publications/Fire%20Book.pdf|title=The Fire Book|publisher=Tangentyre Landcare|year=2005|archive-date=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlannery writes that \"The use of fire by Aboriginal people was so widespread and constant that virtually every early explorer in Australia makes mention of it. It was Aboriginal fire that prompted James Cook to call Australia 'This continent of smoke'.\" However, he goes on to say: \"When control was wrested from the Aborigines and placed in the hands of Europeans, disaster resulted.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=Flannery, Tim|author-link=Tim Flannery|url=https://www.ecobooks.com/books/futureat.htm|title=The Future Eaters: An Ecological History of the Australasian Lands and People|publisher=Grove Press|year=2002|isbn=|page=}}</ref> Fire suppression became the dominant paradigm in fire management leading to a significant shift away from traditional burning practices. A 2001 study found that the disruption of traditional burning practices and the introduction of unrestrained logging meant that many areas of Australia were now prone to extensive wildfires especially in the dry season.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ward, D. J.|author2=Lamont, B. B.|author3=Burrows, C. L.|publication-date=2001|title=Historical role of fire: Grasstrees reveal contrasting fire regimes in eucalypt forest before and after European settlement of southwestern Australia|journal=Forest Ecology and Management|number=150|pages=323\u2013329}}</ref> A similar study in 2017 found that the removal of mature trees by Europeans since they began to settle in Australia may have triggered extensive shrub regeneration which presents a much greater fire fuel hazard.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Relationships between mature trees and fire fuel hazard in Australian forest|first1=Nicholas|last1=Wilson|first2=Geoffrey J.|last2=Cary|first3=Philip|last3=Gibbons|date=15 June 2018|journal=International Journal of Wildland Fire|volume=27|issue=5|pages=353\u2013362|doi=10.1071/WF17112|hdl=1885/160659}}</ref> Another factor was the introduction of [[Andropogon gayanus|gamba grass]] imported into Queensland as a pasture grass in 1942, and planted on a large scale from 1983. This can fuel intense bushfires, leading to loss of tree cover and long-term environmental damage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gamba grass (''Andropogon gayanus'') |url=http://www.daff.qld.gov.au/plants/weeds-pest-animals-ants/weeds/a-z-listing-of-weeds/photo-guide-to-weeds/gamba-grass |work=A\u2013Z listing of weeds: Photo guide to weeds |publisher=Queensland Department of Primary Industries}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Head, Lesley|author1-link=Lesley Head|author2=Atchison, Jennifer|year=2015|title=Governing invasive plants: Policy and practice in managing the Gamba grass (Andropogon gayanus) \u2013 Bushfire nexus in northern Australia|journal=Land Use Policy|number=47|pages=225\u2013234}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:WP Black Thursday.jpg|thumb|400px|A depiction of the 1851 [[Black Thursday bushfires]] in Victoria]]\n\nAustralia's hot, arid climate and wind-driven bushfires were a new and frightening phenomenon to the European settlers of the colonial era. The devastating Victorian bushfires of 1851, remembered as the [[Black Thursday bushfires]], burned in a chain from [[Portland, Victoria|Portland]] to [[Gippsland]], and sent smoke billowing across the Bass Strait to north west Tasmania, where terrified settlers huddled around candles in their huts under a blackened afternoon sky.<ref name=Blainey/>{{rp|386\u2013387}} The fires covered five million hectares (around one quarter of what is now the state of Victoria). Portland, Plenty Ranges, Westernport, the Wimmera and Dandenong districts were badly hit, and around twelve lives were recorded lost, along with one million sheep and thousands of cattle.<ref name=FFM>{{cite web |url=https://www.ffm.vic.gov.au/history-and-incidents/past-bushfires |work=Forest Fire Management Victoria|title=Past bushfires|publisher=Government of Victoria|accessdate=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nNew arrivals from the wetter climes of Britain and Ireland learned painful lessons in fire management and the European farmers slowly began to adapt - growing green crops around their haystacks and burning fire breaks around their pastures, and becoming cautious about burn offs of wheatfield stubble and ringbarked trees.<ref name=Blainey/>{{rp|387}} But major fire events persisted, including South Gippsland's 1898 [[Red Tuesday bushfires]] that burned {{convert|260000|ha}} and claimed twelve lives and more than 2,000 buildings.<ref name=FFM/>\n\n===20th century===\n\nLarge bushfires continued throughout the 20th century. With increasing population and urban spread into bushland came increasing death tolls and property damage during large fires.<ref name=Cheney/>\n\n====1925-6: Gippsland fires and Black Sunday====\n\nDuring the [[1925\u201326 Victorian bushfire season]], large areas of [[Gippsland]] in Victoria caught fire, leading to the Black Sunday fires on 14 February, when 31 people were killed in [[Warburton, Victoria|Warburton]], near Melbourne. These fires remain the fifth most deadly bushfires recorded, with 60 people killed over two months.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/>\n\n====1938-9 season and Black Friday====\n[[File:Black Friday 1939.jpg|thumb|Extent of the 1939 [[Black Friday bushfires]] in Victoria]]\n\nThe 1939 fire season was one of the worst on record for Australia, peaking with Victoria's devastating [[Black Friday bushfires]] of 13 January, but enduring for the full summer, with fires burning the urban fringes of Sydney, Melbourne and Canberra, and ash falling as far away as New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6146527/hg-wells-and-the-big-chill-in-canberras-1939-heatwave/ |title=H.G Wells and the big chill in Canberra's 1939 heatwave|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=20 January 2014|accessdate= }}</ref> The Black Friday fires were the third deadliest on record, with some 71 people killed and 650 houses destroyed.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/> They followed years of drought and a series of extreme heatwaves that were accompanied by strong northerly winds, after a very dry six months. Melbourne hit {{convert|45.6|C|F}} and Adelaide {{convert|46.1|C|F}}. In NSW, Bourke suffered 37 consecutive days above 38 degrees and Menindee hit a record {{convert|49.7|C|F}} on 10 January.<ref name=\"lessons\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/environment/climate-change/lessons-learnt-and-perhaps-forgotten-from-australia-s-worst-fires-20190108-p50qol.html |title=Lessons learnt (and perhaps forgotten) from Australia's 'worst fires'|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=11 January 2019|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nNew South Wales also lost hundreds of houses, thousands of stock and poultry, and thousands of hectares of grazing land.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush Fires Over Wide Area|work=The Argus|date=16 January 1939|page=}}</ref>  By 16 January, disastrous fires were burning in Victoria, New South Wales and the ACT at the climax of a terrible heatwave. Sydney was ringed to the north, south and west by fires from Palm Beach and Port Hacking to the Blue Mountains. Fires blazing at Castle Hill, Sylvania, Cronulla and French's Forest in the city.<ref name=\"lessons\"/><ref name=terrible>{{cite news|title=Terrible Climax to Heatwave|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 January 1939|page=}}</ref> Disastrous fires were also reported at Penrose, Wollongong, Nowra, Bathurst, Ulludulla, Mittagong, Trunkey and Nelligen.<ref name=terrible/> Meanwhile, Canberra faced the \"worst bushfires\" it had experienced, with thousands of hectares burned and a {{convert|45|mi|km|adj=on|order=flip}} fire front driven towards the city by a south westerly gale, destroying pine plantations and many homesteads, and threatening [[Mount Stromlo Observatory]], Government House, and [[Black Mountain (Australian Capital Territory)|Black Mountain]]. Large numbers of men were sent to stand by government buildings in the line of fire.<ref name=terrible/>\n\n; Black Friday\n\nThe state of Victoria was hardest hit, with an area of almost two million hectares burned, 71 people killed, and whole townships wiped out, along with many sawmills and thousands of sheep, cattle and horses around [[Black Friday bushfires|Black Friday]]. Fires had been burning through December, but linked up with devastating force on Friday 13 January, plunging many areas of the state into midday blackness.<ref name=\"RC 1939\">{{cite web|url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-52798639/view?partId=nla.obj-95600830#page/n4/mode/1up|title=Report of the Royal Commission: Introduction - Part 1|publisher=Victorian Government|date=1939|via=Trove, [[National Library of Australia]]|accessdate= }}</ref> The Stretton Royal Commission later wrote wrote:<ref name=\"RC 1939\"/>\n\n{{blockquote|\"On [13 January] it appeared that the whole State was alight. At midday, in many places, it was dark as night. Men carrying hurricane lamps, worked to make safe their families and belongings. Travellers on the highways were trapped by fires or blazing fallen trees, and perished. Throughout the land there was daytime darkness... Steel girders and machinery were twisted by heat as if they had been of fine wire. Sleepers of heavy durable timber, set in the soil, their upper surfaces flush with the ground, were burnt through... Where the fire was most intense the soil was burnt to such a depth that it may be many years before it shall have been restored...\"|Stretton Royal Commission.}}\n\nThe townships of Warrandyte, Yarra Glen, Omeo and Pomonal were badly damaged, and fires burned to the urban fringe of Melbourne, affecting towns including Toolangi, Warburton and Thomson Valley. In the Victorian Alps, the towns of Bright, Cudgewa and Corryong were also hit, along with vast areas in the west, in particular Portland, the Otway Ranges and the Grampians. Black Range, Rubicon, Acheron, Noojee, Tanjil Bren, Hill End, Woods Point, Matlock, Erica, Omeo, Toombullup and the Black Forest were also affected. Huge amounts of smoke and ash were generated, with reports of ash falling as far away as New Zealand.<ref name=FFM/>\n\n; Legacy\n\nAfter the bushfires, Victoria convened a [[Royal Commission]]. Judge Leonard Stretton was instructed to inquire into the causes of the fires, and consider the measures taken to prevent the fires and to protect life and property. He made seven major recommendations to improve forest and fire management, and planned burning became an official fire management practice.<ref name=\"Black Friday 1939\">{{cite web|title=Black Friday 1939|url=https://www.ffm.vic.gov.au/history-and-incidents/black-friday-1939|work=Forest Fire Management Victoria|publisher=\u00a9 State of Victoria (Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning)|accessdate=19 January 2020 |language=en-AU|date=27 February 2017}} [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n\n====1966-7 and Black Tuesday====\n[[File:SmokeStreetsHobart1967.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hobart]] filled with smoke during the [[1967 Tasmanian fires]].]]\n\nIn the summer of 1967, Tasmania suffered its [[1967 Tasmanian fires|most destructive fire season]], and Australia's fourth most deadly on record. A verdant spring had added higher than usual fuel to the state's forest floors, and strong northerly winds and high temperatures drove at least 80 different fires across the south-east, burning to within {{convert|2|km}} of the centre of Hobart, the state capital. The infernos killed 62 people and destroyed almost 1300 homes.<ref name=\"Australian Geographic\"/>\n\n====1993-4 Sydney and NSW eastern seaboard bushfires====\n[[File:Sydney bushfire.jpg|thumb|A pall of bushfire smoke over Sydney during the [[1994 Eastern seaboard fires]].]]\n\nFrom 27 December 1993 to 16 January 1994, [[1994 Eastern seaboard fires|over 800 severe fires]] burned along the coastal areas of New South Wales, affecting the state's most populous regions. Blazes emerged from the Queensland border down the north and central coast, through the Sydney basin and down the south coast to [[Batemans Bay]]. The {{convert|800000|ha|acre|adj=on}} spread of fires were generally contained within less than {{convert|100|km}} from the coast, and many burned through rugged and largely uninhabited country in national parks or nature reserves.<ref name=Cheney>{{cite web|author1=Cheney, N. P.|author2=CSIRO Division of Forestry|url=https://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/6C98BB75496A5AD1CA2569DE00267E48|title=BUSHFIRES - AN INTEGRAL PART OF AUSTRALIA'S ENVIRONMENT|work=The Year Book of Australia 1995|publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics|date=1995|accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref> Dramatic scenes of the city of Sydney shrouded in thick bushfire smoke, and bushland suburbs on fire were broadcast around the world.<ref name=RFS>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/our-districts/mia/photovideo-gallery/2014-photovideo-gallery/twenty-years-on-since-the-1994-fires-seven-news-flashback|title=Twenty years on since the 1994 fires|work=Seven News Flashback|publisher=New South Wales Rural Fire Service|date=6 January 2014|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December, the Dept of Bushfire Services was monitoring more than a dozen fires around the state, and homes were threatened in Turramurra by a fire in the Lane Cove River reserve, and a scrub fire had briefly cut off the holiday village of Bundeena in the [[Royal National Park]], south of Sydney.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bushfire threatens homes in Turramurra|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=29 December 1993|accessdate=|page=}}</ref> ''[[The Age]]'' reported on 7 January that one quarter of NSW was under threat in the worst fires seen in the state for nearly fifty years, as hundreds of firefighters from interstate joined 4000 NSW firefighters battling blazes from Batemans Bay to Grafton. Fires in the Lane Cove River area at Marsfield, Turramurra, West Pymble and Macquarie Park were threatening hundreds of homes, and the fire in the Royal National Park raged toward Bundeena, where rescue boats evacuated 3100 people caught in the path of the fire. With the Prime Minister [[Paul Keating]] on leave, Deputy Prime Minister [[Brian Howe (politician)|Brian Howe]], ordered 100 soldiers to join firefighting efforts, and placed a further 100 on standby.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands flee path of advancing flames|work=The Sunday Age|date=9 January 1994|accessdate=|page=}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January, the Royal National Park fire swept into the southern Sydney suburbs of [[Como West, New South Wales|Como]] and [[Jannali, New South Wales|Jannali]] where many homes would be destroyed, along with two schools a church and a kindergarten.<ref name=\"war diary\">{{cite news|title=War Diary of a State Ablaze|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=15 January 1994|accessdate=|page=}}</ref><ref name=\"leader-20-years-on\">{{cite news|last1=Mutton|first1=Sheree |title=Shire fire horror still lingers 20 years on |url=http://www.theleader.com.au/story/2012100/shire-fire-horror-still-lingers-20-years-on/ |accessdate=22 January 2018 |work=[[St George & Sutherland Shire Leader]]|date=9 January 2014}}</ref> The Como/Jannali fire burnt {{convert|476|ha}} and destroyed 101 houses - more than half of the total homes lost in New South Wales during the January emergency period.<ref name=Cheney/> Also on 8 January, fires had reached to within {{convert|1.5|km}} of Gosford city centre, and some 5000 people had been evacuated over that weekend with homes destroyed at Somersby and Peats Ridge.<ref name=\"war diary\"/>\n\nBy 9 January, more than 16,000 people were on standby for evacuation from the Lower Blue Mountains. Thousands of people were sleeping on the football field at the Central Coast Leagues Club, after the evacuation of Kariong, Woy Woy, Umina, Ettalong and Brisbane Waters. Much of Gosford, Kariong and Somersby had been evacuated, along with Terry Hill. Homes at Menai, Sutherland, Chatswood, Lindfield, Turramurra, Macquarie Park and Sydney's northern beaches had been lost. 60 fires were burning on the north coast, as firefighters battled infernos over {{convert|30|ha}} from Coffs Harbour to the Queensland border. Fires were approaching towns in the Blue Mountains including Blackheath and in the Shoalhaven, including Ulladulla.<ref>{{cite news|title=A round up of all the fire regions|work=The Age|page=2|date=9 January 1994|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n; Legacy\n\nSome 20,000 firefighters were deployed against around 800 fires mainly along the coast and ranges. The fires caused mass evacuations, claimed four lives, destroyed some 225 homes and burnt {{convert|800000|ha|acres}} of bushland. They were met with amongst the largest firefighting efforts in Australian history. A lengthy Coronial inquest followed the fires, leading to the formation of the [[New South Wales Rural Fire Service]].<ref name=RFS/> The ''Rural Fires Act 1997'' was proclaimed on 1 September 1997.<ref name=RFS/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/history|work=NSW Rural Fire Service|title=Our History|date=n.d.|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nBetween 1 November 2019 and 31 January 2020, Australia had one of the worst bush fires in history. The deadliest bushfire disaster was that of \"Black Saturday\" in February 2009 when 180 people died in Victoria. 2019 had been the hottest record year for Australia. Fires have raged near the Australian capital Canberra for weeks, and had shut down the city's airports as flames approached the perimeter. A little more than 24 and a half million acres that have been affected can compare to the 32 million acres of England. Grass fires typically can spread around 14 miles per hour.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50951043|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Australia fires: A visual guide to the bushfire crisis|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Northern Australia ===\nIn the last ten years or so,{{when|date=February 2020}} government licenses have been granted to fire-prevention programs on Aboriginal lands in northern Australia. In this area Aboriginal traditions, which reduce the undergrowth that can fuel bigger blazes, revolve around the monsoon. Land is burned patch by patch using \"cool\" fires in targeted areas during the early dry season, between March and July.<ref name=\"Guardian-Allam-2020-01-18\">{{cite news|author=Allam, Lorena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/19/right-fire-for-right-future-how-cultural-burning-can-protect-australia-from-catastrophic-blazes|title=Right fire for right future: how cultural burning can protect Australia from catastrophic blazes|work=[[Guardian Australia]]|date=18 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> These defensive burning programs began in the 1980s and 1990s when Aboriginal groups moved back onto their native lands. Since this process began, destructive bushfires in northern Australia have burned 57% fewer acres in 2019 than they did on average in the years from 2000 to 2010, the decade before the program started.<ref>{{cite news|author=Fuller, Thomas|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12301169|title=Reducing fire, and cutting carbon emissions, the Aboriginal way|work=[[New York Times]]|via=[[NZ Herald]]|date=17 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOliver Costello from the national Indigenous Firesticks Alliance stated that in southern Australia, Aboriginal knowledge systems of fire management are less valued than in the north. In the [[Kimberley, Western Australia|Kimberley area]], the land council applies local resources and holds community fire planning meetings to ensure the correct people are doing the burning. Burn lines are approved by the group but [[Indigenous ranger]]s set the fires, backed up by modern technology involving constant weather readings and taking into account the conditions of the day. Costello pointed out that northern Australia has developed a collaborative infrastructure for 'cultural burning' and noted that: \"There\u2019s no investment really outside of northern Australia Indigenous fire management of any significance.\"<ref name=\"Guardian-Allam-2020-01-18\"/>\n\n== Factors and causes ==\n=== Ignition ===\nIn recent times most major bush fires have been started in remote areas by dry lightning<ref>{{Cite news|author1=Nguyen, Kevin|author2= Brunero, Tim|author3=Thomas, Sarah|author4=Keane, Daniel|author5=Mills, Nicole|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-11/australias-fires-reveal-arson-not-a-major-cause/11855022|title=The truth about Australia's fires \u2014 arsonists aren't responsible for many this season|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=18 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author1=RMIT ABC Fact Check|author2=Gordon, Josh|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-15/is-arson-mostly-to-blame-for-the-bushfire-crisis/11865724|title=Some Coalition MPS say arson is mostly to blame for the bushfire crisis. Here are the facts|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=14 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> or by electric power lines being brought down or arcing in high winds.  Many fires are as a result of either deliberate arson or carelessness, however these fires normally happen in readily accessible areas and are rapidly brought under control.  Man-made events include [[electric arc|arcing]] from overhead power lines, arson, accidental ignition in the course of agricultural clearing, grinding and welding activities, campfires, cigarettes and dropped matches, sparks from machinery, and [[controlled burn]] escapes. They spread based on the type and quantity of fuel that is available. Fuel can include everything from trees, underbrush and dry grassy fields to homes. Wind supplies the fire with additional oxygen pushing the fire across the land at a faster rate.\n\nLarge, violent wildfires can generate winds of their own, called fire whirls. Fire whirls are like tornadoes and result from the vortices created by the fire's heat. When these vortices are tilted from horizontal to vertical, this creates fire whirls. These whirls have been known to hurl flaming logs and burning debris over considerable distances.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bonsor, Kevin|url=https://science.howstuffworks.com/nature/natural-disasters/wildfire1.htm|title=How Wildfires Work|work=How Stuff Works|date=29 May 2001|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome reports indicate that a changing climate could also be contributing to the ferocity of the 2019\u201320 fires with hotter, drier conditions making the country's fire season longer and much more dangerous.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/climate-and-people/australia-burning-bushfires-bad/|title=Australia is burning \u2013 but why are the bushfires so bad and is climate change to blame?|first=Sarah|last=Newey|date=2 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> Strong winds also promote the rapid spread of fires by lifting burning embers into the air. This is known as spotting and can start a new fire up to {{convert|40|km}} downwind from the fire front.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fire Behaviour|url=https://www.thebushfirefoundation.org/how-fire-behaves/|website=The Bushfire Foundation|date=2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> In the Northern Territory fires can also be spread by black kites, whistling kites and brown falcons. These birds have been spotted picking up burning twigs, flying to areas of unburned grass and dropping them to start new fires there. This exposes their prey attempting to flee the blazes: small mammals, birds, lizards, and insects.<ref name=\"BBC_22Nov2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50511963|title=Australia bushfires: Which animals typically fare best and worst?|work=[[BBC News]]|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nMonths of severe drought and record-breaking temperatures have fueled a series of massive bush fires across Australia. Hot and windy conditions had authorities of Australian Capital Territory declare a state of emergency.\n\n[[File:Fire activity swifts creek 2007 edit.jpg|thumb|800px|center|Looking towards [[Dargo, Victoria]] from [[Swifts Creek, Victoria|Swifts Creek]], 11 January 2006]]\n\n===Topography===\n[[File:Prospect Hill bushfires.jpg|thumb|220px|A hilly bushfire that charred [[Prospect Hill (New South Wales)|Prospect Hill]], in [[Sydney]].]]\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\nBushfires in Australia are generally described as uncontrolled, non-structural fires burning in a grass, [[Shrubland|scrub]], bush, or forested area. The nature of the fire depends somewhat on local [[topography]]. Hilly/mountainous fires burn in areas which are usually densely forested. The land is less accessible and not conducive to agriculture, thus many of these densely forested areas have been saved from [[deforestation]] and are protected by national, state and other parks. The steep terrain increases the speed and intensity of a firestorm. Where settlements are located in hilly or mountainous areas, bushfires can pose a threat to both life and property. Flat/grassland fires burn along flat plains or areas of small undulation, predominantly covered in grasses or scrubland. These fires can move quickly, fanned by high winds in flat topography, and they quickly consume the small amounts of fuel/vegetation available. These fires pose less of a threat to settlements as they rarely reach the same intensity seen in major firestorms as the land is flat, the fires are easier to map and predict, and the terrain is more accessible for [[firefighting]] personnel. Many regions of predominantly flat terrain in Australia have been almost completely deforested for agriculture, reducing the fuel loads which would otherwise facilitate fires in these areas.\n\n=== Climate change ===\n{{See also| Climate change in Australia}}\nAustralia's climate has warmed by more than one degree Celsius over the past century, causing an increase in the frequency and intensity of heatwaves and droughts.<ref name=\"ScientificAmerican\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/australias-angry-summer-this-is-what-climate-change-looks-like/|title=Australia's Angry Summer: This Is What Climate Change Looks Like|author=Abram, Nerilie|author-link=Nerilie Abram|date=31 December 2019|work=Scientific American|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> Eight of Australia's ten warmest years on record have occurred since 2005.<ref name=stuff>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/climate-news/118568474/australia-bushfires-spew-twothirds-of-national-carbon-emissions-in-one-season|title=Australia bushfires spew two-thirds of national carbon emissions in one season|work=Stuff|location=New Zealand|date=3 January 2019|accessdate=}}</ref> A study in 2018 conducted at Melbourne University found that the major droughts of the late 20th century and early 21st century in southern Australia are \"likely without precedent over the past 400 years\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Freund, Mandy|author2=Henley, Ben|author3=Allen, Kathryn|author4=Baker, Patrick|url=https://theconversation.com/recent-australian-droughts-may-be-the-worst-in-800-years-94292|title=Recent Australian droughts may be the worst in 800 years|work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|author= |date=2 May 2018|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Across the country, the average summer temperatures have increased leading to record-breaking hot weather,<ref name=\"auto\"/> with the early summer of 2019 the hottest on record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tai.org.au/sites/default/files/Climate%20of%20the%20Nation%202019%20%5BWEB%5D.pdf|title=Climate of the Nation|year=2019|publisher=The Australia Institute|page=3|issn=|accessdate=}}</ref> 2019 was also Australia's driest ever year since 1900 with rainfall 40% lower than average.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|author=Readfearn, Graham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/jan/13/explainer-what-are-the-underlying-causes-of-australias-shocking-bushfire-season|title=Explainer: what are the underlying causes of Australia's shocking bushfire season?|work=Guardian Australia|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHeatwaves and droughts dry out the undergrowth and create conditions that increase the risk of bushfires. This has become worse in the last 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.climateinstitute.org.au/verve/_resources/bushfirenationalbrief.pdf|title=Bushfire weather in Southeast Australia: Media Brief|work=The Climate Institute|date=26 September 2007|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> Since the mid-1990s, southeast Australia has experienced a 15% decline in late autumn and early winter rainfall and a 25% decline in average rainfall in April and May. Rainfall for January to August 2019 was the lowest on record in the Southern Downs (Queensland) and Northern Tablelands (New South Wales) with some areas 77% below the long term average.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/not-normal-climate-change-bushfire-web/ |title=The Facts about Bushfires and Climate Change|publisher=Climate Council|location=Australia|date=13 November 2019|accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) concluded that ongoing anthropogenic climate change was virtually certain to increase in intensity and frequency of fires in Australia \u2013 a conclusion that has been endorsed in numerous reports since.<ref name=ScientificAmerican/> In November 2019, the Australian Climate Council published a report titled ''This is Not Normal''<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/resources/bushfire-briefing-paper/|title=This is Not Normal: Climate Change and Escalating bushfire risk|last=Colton|first=Schroeder|date=12 November 2019|website=|publisher=Climate Council|location=Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> which also found the catastrophic bushfire conditions affecting NSW and Queensland in late 2019 have been aggravated by climate change.<ref name=\"auto\"/> According to [[Nerilie Abram]] writing in ''[[Scientific American]]'' \"the link between the current extremes and anthropogenic climate change is scientifically indisputable\".<ref name=ScientificAmerican/> In 2020, an international team of scientists found the hot and dry conditions that helped drive Australia\u2019s 2019-2020 bushfire crisis would be eight times more likely to happen if the earth warms by 2C.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/05/bushfire-crisis-conditions-eight-times-more-likely-under-2c-warming-analysis-shows Bushfire crisis conditions eight times more likely under 2C warming, analysis shows], The Guardian, 4 March 2020</ref>\n\n=== Carbon emissions ===\n{{Main|Greenhouse gas emissions by Australia}}\nUntil the [[2019\u20132020 Australian bushfire season]], the forests in Australia were thought to reabsorb all the carbon released in bushfires across the country. This would mean the forests achieved net-zero emissions. However, scientists now say that global warming is making bushfires burn more intensely and frequently and believe the 2019-2020 fires have already released approximately {{convert|350|e6t|e6ST|abbr=off}} of carbon dioxide \u2013 as much as two-thirds of Australia's average annual carbon dioxide emissions ({{convert|530|e6t|e6ST|abbr=off}} in 2017)<ref>{{cite book|title=National Inventory by Economic Sector 2017|work=Australia\u2019s National Greenhouse Accounts|publisher=[[Department of the Environment and Energy]]|date=August 2019|page=3|url=|isbn=|accessdate=}}</ref> in just the past three months. David Bowman, professor of [[pyrogeography]] and fire science at the University of Tasmania warned that so much damage has been done that Australian forests may take more than 100 years to re-absorb the carbon that has been released so far this fire season.<ref name=stuff/>\n\nIn January 2020, the [[Met Office|British Met Office]] said Australia's bushfires in 2019-2020 were expected to contribute 2% to the increase in the atmospheric concentration of major greenhouse gases which are forecast to hit 417 parts per million, one of the largest annual increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide on record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/24/australian-bushfires-to-contribute-to-huge-annual-increase-in-global-carbon-dioxide|title=Australian bushfires to contribute to huge annual increase in global carbon dioxide|work=Guardian Australia|date=24 January 2020|accessdate= }}</ref> Climate studies show that conditions which promote extreme bushfires in Australia will only get worse as more greenhouse gases are added to the atmosphere.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nThe smoke from the fire has created a major pollution hazard, dropping air quality to rating the third worst of all major global cities, according to Swiss-based group AirVisual. Plumes of black carbon have traveled more than 7,000 miles from the fires. Black carbon is harmful to human health and contributes to climate change. \n\n=== Seasonality ===\nBushfires in Australia can occur all year-round, though the severity and the \"bushfire season\" varies by region.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Luke R. H.|author2=McArthur, A. G.|year=1978|title=Bushfires in Australia|publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service|location=Canberra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gQhbkWRlPIW1pumwsHDkWeia8l_QD968SJR80|title=Hot and dry Australia sees wildfire danger rise|last=Sullivan|first=Rohan|date=11 February 2009|publisher=The Association Press|access-date=13 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://burarra.questacon.edu.au/pages/seasons.html | title=Monsoonal Climate | accessdate=9 September 2006 | publisher=Questacon | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320141721/http://burarra.questacon.edu.au/pages/seasons.html | archive-date=20 March 2012 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere is no formal definition for a single bushfire season across the whole of Australia.  There is no one terminology used for periods of fire activity.  The technical terms used for periods of fire risk and fire activity include fire weather season,<ref name=\"bom2020\"/> fire danger season,<ref name=\"bom2020\"/><ref name=\"sacfs2020\"/> bush fire danger period,<ref name=\"nswrfs2020a\"/> fire danger period,<ref name=\"viccfa2020\"/><ref name=\"ntg2020b\"/> fire permit period,<ref name=\"tassfc2020\"/> restricted burning times, and, prohibited burning times,<ref name=\"wabfa1954\"/> and fire season.<ref name=\"ntg2020a\"/>\n\nThe term \"Australian bushfire season\", is a {{linktext|colloquialism}} broadly defined by common usage, from when the first uncontrolled fires start any time from June onwards,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Lucas, Chris|author2=Harris, Sarah|url=https://theconversation.com/its-only-october-so-whats-with-all-these-bushfires-new-research-explains-it-124091|title=It\u2019s only October, so what\u2019s with all these bushfires? New research explains it|work=[[The Conversation]]|date=10 October 2019|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> typically shortened to \"bushfire season\", and applies mainly to southern and eastern Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/7.30/early-start-to-bushfire-season-in-nsw-catches-many/11494054|title=Early start to bushfire season in NSW catches many by surprise|work=7:30|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=9 September 2019|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-12-04/gippsland-warned-of-long-bushfire-season/11755562|title=Bushfire season starts early with Gippsland residents urged to prepare after deadly 'practice run'|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=4 December 2019|author=Maunder, Sarah|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.northerndailyleader.com.au/story/6269553/warmer-temperatures-mean-bushfire-season-could-come-early-again/|title=Bushfire season could hit Australia early following warmer temperatures|work=Northern Daily Leader|date=12 July 2019|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> It can continue through to April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/our-districts/cudgegong/latest-news/bush-fire-danger-period-extended-until-30-april-2019|title=Bush Fire Danger Period Extended until 30 April 2019|publisher=NSW Rural Fire Service|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> Central and northern Australia have two separately defined fire seasons.<ref name=\"ntg2020a\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/rural/2013-10-31/average-fire-season-for-central-australia/5060802?site=alicesprings|title=Central Australia set for 'average' fire season\n|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=31 October 2013|author=Brown, Carmen|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> The colloqial term is typically used in conjunction with the technical terms when conveying information to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southernhighlandnews.com.au/story/6329695/bushfire-season-starts-early/|title=Bushfire season starts early|work=Southern Highland News|date=15 August 2019|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hawkesbury.nsw.gov.au/media/forms/open-burning|title=Open Burning|publisher=Hawkesbury City Council|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian [[Bureau of Meteorology]] defines five \"fire danger seasons\", being times of peak bushfire activity, roughly corresponding to broad bands of latitude across the Australian continent<ref name=\"bom2020\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/weather-services/fire-weather-centre/bushfire-weather/index.shtml|title=Bushfire weather|publisher=Bureau of Meteorology, Australia|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> including winter and spring, across the most northern parts of Australia; spring; spring and summer; summer; and summer and autumn, across the most southern parts of Australia.\n\nEach Australian state and territory jurisdiction defines periods of peak fire risk or fire activity differently. [[New South Wales]] has a default statutory \"bush fire danger period\" defined in law, from 1 October to 31 March.<ref name=\"nswrfs2020a\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/BFDP|title=Bush Fire Danger Period and Fire Permits|publisher=NSW Rural Fire Service|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The state government can then declare different start and end dates for bush fire danger periods for each local government area within the state. In 2019 these started 1 August.<ref name=\"nswrfs2019b\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/news-and-media/media-releases/nsw-rfs-declares-start-of-bush-fire-danger-period|title=NSW RFS declares start of Bush Fire Danger Period|publisher=NSW Rural Fore Service|date=1 August 2019|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] declares a \"fire danger period\" for each local government area. Victorian fire danger periods typically start in October and finish as late as May.<ref name=\"viccfa2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/warnings-restrictions/restrictions-during-the-fire-danger-period|title=Restrictions During the Fire Danger Period|publisher=Country Fire Association|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The [[Government of South Australia|South Australia Government]] declares a \"fire danger season\" for each local government area, potentially starting in October and finishing at the end of April.<ref name=\"sacfs2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfs.sa.gov.au/site/bans_and_ratings/fire_danger_season_dates.jsp|title=Fire Danger Season Dates|publisher=South Australian Country Fire Service|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The [[Government of Tasmania|Tasmanian Government]] declares \"fire permit period\"s for local government areas. In 2019 this commenced 31 October.<ref name=\"tassfc2020\">{{cite web|url=https://messages.fire.tas.gov.au/sites/default/files/filefield_paths/-TFS%20Fire%20Permit%20Period%20Declaration.pdf|title=Fire Permit Period Declaration|publisher=State Fire Commission, Tasmania|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> [[Western Australia]] requires each local government area to declare its own \"restricted burning times\" roughly aligned with spring and autumn, and \"prohibited burning times\" roughly aligned with summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waroona.wa.gov.au/services/emergency-services/fire-control-information.aspx|title=Fire Control Information 2019/20|publisher=Waroona Shire Council|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.donnybrook-balingup.wa.gov.au/services/fire-emergency-management.aspx|title=Fire|publisher=Donnybrook Belingup Shire|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wabfa1954\">{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.wa.gov.au/legislation/prod/filestore.nsf/FileURL/mrdoc_41660.htm/$FILE/Bush%20Fires%20Act%201954%20-%20%5B09-h0-01%5D.html?OpenElement|title=Bush Fires Act 1954 - Western Australia|publisher=Government of Western Australia|date=1954|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The [[Northern Territory]] defines two broad \"fire seasons\", a northern fire season, which can run from April to November, and a central Australian fire season, which can run from October to March.<ref name=\"ntg2020a\">{{cite web|url=https://securent.nt.gov.au/prepare-for-an-emergency/bushfires/fire-management-in-the-nt|title=Fire management in the NT|publisher=Northern Territory Government|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref> The Government also refers to these as \"fire danger periods\".<ref name=\"ntg2020b\">{{cite web|url=https://denr.nt.gov.au/news/2019/central-australian-fire-season-commencement|title=Central Australian fire season commencement|date=4 December 2019|publisher=Northern Territory Government|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nBushfire seasons are commonly grouped into years such as \"[[2019\u20132020 Australian bushfire season]]\" and typically apply to the season for southern and eastern Australia; from 1 June to 31 May annually.\n\n== Impact on wildlife ==\nBush fires kill animals directly and also destroy local habitats, leaving the survivors vulnerable even once the fires have passed.  Professor Chris Dickman at Sydney University estimates that in the first three months of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|2019\u20132020 bushfires]], over 800&nbsp;million animals died in NSW, and more than one billion nationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sydney.edu.au/news-opinion/news/2020/01/08/australian-bushfires-more-than-one-billion-animals-impacted.html|title=More than one billion animals killed in Australian bushfires|publisher=University of Sydney|date=8 January 2020|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> This figure includes mammals, birds, and reptiles but does not include insects, bats or frogs. Many of these animals were burnt to death in the fires, with many others dying later due to the depletion of food and shelter resources and predation by feral cats and red foxes. Dickman adds that Australia has the highest rate of species loss of any area in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sydney.edu.au/news-opinion/news/2020/01/03/a-statement-about-the-480-million-animals-killed-in-nsw-bushfire.html|title=A statement about the 480 million animals killed in NSW bushfires since September|publisher=University of Sydney|date=3 January 2020|accessdate=}}</ref> with fears that some of Australia's native species, like the Kangaroo Island dunnart, may even become extinct because of the current fires.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/the-weekend/audio/2018729608/kiwi-volunteers-helping-fire-affected-australian-animals|title=Kiwi volunteers helping fire-affected Australian animals|work=RNZ|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n[[Koala]]s are perhaps the most vulnerable because they are slow-moving. In extreme fires, koalas tend to climb up to the top of a tree and curl into a ball where they become trapped. In January 2020 it was reported that half of the 50,000 koalas on [[Kangaroo Island]] off Australia's southern coast, which are kept separate to those on the mainland as insurance for the species\u2019 future, are thought to have died in the previous few weeks.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/06/kangaroo-koala-australia-bushfires-wildfires-die|title=The world loves kangaroos and koalas. Now we are watching them die in droves|work=Guardian Australia|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nWildlife ecologist Professor Euan Ritchie from Deakin University says that when fires have passed, frogs and [[skink]]s are left vulnerable when their habitats have been destroyed. Loss of habitat also affects already endangered species such as the western ground parrot, the Leadbeater's possum, the Mallee emu-wren (a bird which cannot fly very far), and Gilbert's potoroo. Beekeepers have also lost hives in bushfires.<ref name=\"BBC_22Nov2019\"/>\n\nKangaroos and wallabies can move quickly trying to escape from fires. However, the Guardian reported in January 2020 that dozens, maybe hundreds of kangaroos \"perished in their droves\" as they tried to outrun the flames near Batlow in NSW.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The most resilient animals are those that can burrow or fly. Possums often get singed, but can sometimes hide in tree hollows. Wombats and snakes tend to go underground.<ref name=BBC_22Nov2019/>\n\n[[Goanna]]s can benefit from bushfires. Dickman says: \"In central Australia, we've seen goannas coming out from their burrows after a fire and picking off injured animals \u2013 singed birds, young birds, small mammals, surface-dwelling lizards, and snakes.\"<ref name=BBC_22Nov2019/>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nIn South Australia, Kangaroo Island was devastated when 25,000 Koalas were killed. The island is renowned for its mixture of animal species, and fear that it may never recover its population. Tens of thousands of farm animals, mostly sheep, were also killed in the fire on Kangaroo Island. There are concerns about the survival of endangered species on Kangaroo Island, which include the dunnart (a mouse-like marsupial) and the black glossy cockatoo.\n\n== Impact on humans ==\n\nThe most devastating impact on humans is that bushfires have killed over 800 people since 1851.<ref name=Tronson/> In addition to loss of life, homes, properties, and livestock are destroyed potentially leaving people homeless, traumatised, and without access to electricity, telecommunications and, in some cases, to drinking water.<ref name=\"reuters.com\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-australia-bushfires-insurance/australia-strengthens-bushfire-defenses-as-economic-environmental-costs-mount-idUSKBN1Z601F Australia strengthens bushfire defenses as economic, environmental costs mount], Reuters, 7 January 2020</ref>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n\nAt least 33 people have been killed, 4 of which were firefighters. About 2,000 homes have been destroyed, which has forced thousands to seek shelter elsewhere. Two people have also died on Kangaroo Island in South Australia. More than 80 homes were destroyed in South Australia near Adelaide Hills, as well as one-third of the vineyards that provide grapes for the wine industry.\n\n=== Health ===\nBushfires produce particulate-matter pollution \u2013 airborne particles that are small enough to enter and damage human lung tissue. Following the [[Hazelwood Power Station#Coal mine fire|Hazelwood fire]] in 2014, Fay Johnston, an associate professor of public health at the University of Tasmania's Menzies Institute for Medical Research, says young children exposed to smoke either as infants, toddlers or in the womb develop changes to their lung function. She says: \"Unborn babies exposed to the Hazelwood smoke were more likely to experience coughs or colds two to four years after the fires.\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\">{{cite news|author=McCauley, Dana|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/health-impacts-of-bushfires-won-t-be-known-for-years-experts-say-20200106-p53p87.html|title=Health impacts of bushfires won't be known for years, experts say|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Other studies conducted in Australia show an increase in respiratory diseases among adults stemming from air pollution caused by bushfires.<ref>{{cite news|author=Salinger, Jim|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/08/australia-bushfires-aotearoa-new-zealand-has-become-kikorangi-mawhero-land-of-the-long-pink-cloud|title=Australia's bushfires mean New Zealand has become the land of the long pink cloud|work=Guardian Australia|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of intense smoke and air pollution stemming from the fires, in January 2020 Canberra measured the worst air quality index of any major city in the world. The orange-tinged smoke entered homes and offices buildings across the capital making breathing outside very difficult, forcing businesses and institutions to shut their doors.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Lansdown, Sarah|author2=Whyte, Sally|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6566337/canberra-shuts-down-as-smoke-smothers-city/?cs=14225|title=Canberra shuts down as smoke smothers city|work=The Canberra Times|date=5 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Studies show that residents of highly polluted cities also have an increased risk of heart attack, stroke, and diabetes. Professor Jalaluddin, a chief investigator with the Centre for Air Pollution, Energy and Health Policy Research, says: \"There is increasing evidence around air pollution and (the development of) neurological conditions, for example, Parkinson's disease and Alzheimer's.\"<ref name=\"smh.com.au\"/>\n\nProf David Bowman, director of the Fire Centre Research Hub at the [[University of Tasmania]], referred to the [[2019-2020 Australian bushfire season|2019\u20132020 fires]] as \"absolutely transformative and unprecedented\" in scale and stated, \"It's pretty much a third of the Australian population that has been impacted, with prolonged, episodic exposure and sometimes extreme health impacts.\" Since September 2019, close to 3,000 firefighters have been out every day in NSW battling blazes. The NSW RFS stated that close to 90% of those are unpaid volunteers.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mao, Frances|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50887982|title=Australia fires: The thousands of volunteers fighting the flames|work=BBC News|date=24 December 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> David McBride, associate professor of occupational and environmental medicine at the [[University of Otago]] stated, \"They push themselves to the limit \u2013 they can suffer heat stress, which is a life-threatening injury, and end up with chronic bronchitis and asthma\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Fyfe, James|author2=Wilton, James|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2020/01/australia-bushfires-concern-over-long-term-effects-on-firefighters-health.html|title=Australia bushfires: Concern over long-term effects on firefighters' health|work=NewsHub|location=New Zealand|date=10 January 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Psychological problems ===\nPsychological problems following a major bushfire appear to develop when people have a chance to stop and reflect on their experience. A study of 1,526 people who experienced significant losses in the 1983 Ash Wednesday bushfires found that after 12 months, 42% met the criteria for a psychiatric problem which is double the prevalence in an unaffected community. After twenty months this figure had dropped to 23%.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://oem.bmj.com/content/59/4/215|title=Bushfires: are we doing enough to reduce the human impact?|journal=Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine|volume=59|number=4|author=Sim, M.|date=April 2002|accessdate=13 February 2020|doi=10.1136/oem.59.4.215}}</ref>\n\nA typical example of how people are affected is described by the 2016 fire at [[Yarloop]] in Western Australia. It virtually destroyed the town (population 395) including 180 homes, historic timber workshops, factories, an old church, the old hospital, shops, the hotel, the fire station and a part of the school. Two people died. Damage to infrastructure included the Samson Brook Bridge, Salmon River Bridge and power infrastructure supplying thousands of homes in the area.<ref>{{cite news|author=Young, Emma|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/national/western-australia/emergency-fire-warning-for-waroona-and-preston-beach-20160107-gm0r5l.html|title=WA fires: deadly Waroona blaze contained but not controlled, downgraded to 'advice'|work=WA Today|date=9 January 2016|accessdate=}}</ref> Two years later, people from Yarloop were still suffering from trauma distress from the fire. Apart from the economic losses suffered by those who lived there, the dislocation to their lives was so great that many in the community were doubtful that the town would be rebuilt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bushfirefront.org.au/home/fire-facts/impacts-of-bushfires/|title=Impacts of Bushfires|work=Bushfire Front|date=2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> The [[Government of Western Australia|WA Government]] subsequently spent {{AUD}}64&nbsp;million rebuilding the town and the surrounding communities.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Birch, Laura|author2=Lynch, Jacqueline|author3=Ferguson, Holly|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-22/yarloop-rebuilding-after-devastating-bushfires/11730556|title=Rising from the ashes, Yarloop bounces back after devastating bushfires in 2016|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic impact ===\nEconomic damage from 2009's Black Saturday fires, the costliest in Australia's history, reached an estimated {{AUD}}4.4&nbsp;billion. Moody's Analytics says the cost of the 2019\u20132020 bushfires is likely to exceed even that figure and will cripple consumer confidence and harm industries such as farming and tourism.<ref>{{cite news|author=Butler, Ben|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/08/economic-impact-of-australias-bushfires-set-to-exceed-44bn-cost-of-black-saturday|title=Economic impact of Australia's bushfires set to exceed $4.4bn cost of Black Saturday|work=Guardian Australia|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> Medical bills from the current fires and smoke haze are expected to reach hundreds of millions of dollars with one analysis suggesting disruptions caused by the fire and smoke haze could cost Sydney as much as {{AUD}}50&nbsp;million a day.<ref>{{cite news|author=McDonald, Tim|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-50862349|title=Australia fires: The huge economic cost of Australia's bushfires|work=BBC News|location=United Kingdom|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> The Insurance Council of Australia estimates that claims for damage from the fires would be more than {{AUD}}700&nbsp;million, with claims expected to jump when more fire-hit areas become accessible. In January 2020, it was reported that the [[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group|ANZ]] gauge of consumer confidence fell to its lowest level in more than four years.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/>\n\nIn response to the current fires, the federal government announced that compensation would be paid to volunteer firefighters, military personnel would be deployed to assist, and an {{AUD}}2&nbsp;billion bush fire recovery fund would be established. New South Wales, which has been hardest hit by the crisis, has pledged {{AUD}}1&nbsp;billion focused on repairing infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|author=Heath, Michael|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-08/australian-economy-staggers-under-wildfires-setting-up-stimulus|title=Australian Economy Struck by Wildfires, Setting Up Stimulus|work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg Green]]|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== From 1 November 2019 to 31 January 2020 ==\n \nAbout 27.2 million acres of bush, forest, and parks across Australia have burned. New South Wales and Victoria have been the worst hit states. In New South Wales, fire has affected about 12 and a half million acres. In Victoria, almost 3 million acres have been burned. \n\n== Official inquiries ==\nAfter many major bushfires, state and federal governments have initiated inquiries to see what could be done to address the problem. A parliamentary report from 2010 stated that between 1939 and 2010, there have been at least 18 major bushfire inquiries including state and federal parliamentary committee inquiries, [[Council of Australian Governments|COAG]] reports, coronial inquiries and Royal Commissions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Former_Committees/agric/completed_inquiries/2008-10/bushfires/report/c02|title=Chapter 2 \u2013 Previous bushfire inquiries|work=The incidence and severity of bushfires across Australia|author=Senate Select Committee on Agricultural and Related Industries|publisher=Parliament of Australia|date=13 August 2010|access-date=15 February 2020|page=|isbn=978-1-74229-349-3}}</ref> Another report published in 2015 stated there have been 51 inquiries into wildfires and wildfire management since 1939. The authors noted that Royal Commissions were not the most effective way to learn from past bushfire events.<ref>{{cite conference |url=https://www.bnhcrc.com.au/file/4881/download?token=PFQPk5fa|title=Learning from Adversity: What has 75 years of bushfire inquiries (1939-2013) taught us?, Report no 2015.019|author1=Eburn, Michael|author1-link=|author2=Hudson, David|author3=Chal, Ignatious|author4=Dovers, Stephen|date=2 September 2014|conference=Research Forum at the Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC & AFAC conference|conference-url= |editor= |others=[[Australian National University]]|volume= |edition= |book-title= |publisher=Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC|archive-url= |archive-date= |location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]]|pages= |format=requires download |id= |isbn= |bibcode= |oclc= |doi= |access-date=15 February 2020|quote=''The fact that catastrophic events continue to recur is evidence either that the community is failing to learn the lessons from the past, or the inquiries fail to identify the true learning \u2013 that catastrophic events may be inevitable, or that Royal Commissions are not the most effective way to identify relevant lessons from past events.''|ref= |postscript= |language=en-AU|page=4 |at= |trans-title= }}</ref> Many of the inquiries into bushfires have recommended \"hazard reduction burning\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Bonyhady, Nick|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/prime-minister-says-hazard-reduction-burns-are-climate-action-20200121-p53tha.html|title=Prime Minister says hazard reduction burns as important as emissions|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> intended to reduce the available fuel and have set targets to burn a certain percentage of forest each year to reduce risk. Planned burns are  difficult to do safely and many of the investigations and Royal Commissions have found these targets are seldom met. At the same time, fire management experts disagree on how effective planned burning is.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mannix, Liam|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/these-scientists-think-we-re-in-a-bushfire-spiral-they-have-a-plan-20200123-p53u68.html|title=These scientists think we're in a 'bushfire spiral'. They have a plan|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 January 2020|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, during the 2019\u20132020 bushfire season, Prime Minister Scott Morrison raised the prospect of establishing another royal commission. In an interview on [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC-TV]] ''[[7.30]]'', Morrison stated that any inquiry into the crisis would need to be comprehensive and investigate climate change as well as other possible causes.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Morrison |first=Scott |subject= |subject-link=Scott Morrison |last2= |first2= |subject2= |subject-link2= |last3= |first3= |subject3= |subject-link3= |last4= |first4= |subject4= |subject-link4= |interviewer=[[Michael Rowland (news presenter)|Michael Rowland]] |title=Scott Morrison defends the Government's response to the bushfires |type= |url=https://www.abc.net.au/7.30/scott-morrison-defends-the-governments-response-to/11856618 |format=Streaming video |work=[[7.30]] |publisher=[[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC-TV]]|location= |date=9 January 2020 |year= |page= |pages= |access-date=15 February 2020 |archive-url= |archive-date= |url-status= |quote=''... there will be a time, I think, to ensure that we work with the states and territories to get the proper inquiry in place. It needs to be comprehensive, it needs to deal with contributing factors which is everything from hazard reduction to climate change through to the response issues, the national coordination matters and, of course, resilience and planning for the future.''}}</ref>\n\n== Warnings ==\nDuring the fire season, the [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology (BOM)]] provides fire weather forecasts. Fire agencies determine the appropriate Fire Danger Rating by considering the predicted weather including temperature, relative humidity, wind speed and dryness of vegetation. These Fire Danger Ratings are a feature of weather forecasts and alert the community to the actions they should take in preparation for the day. Ratings are broadcast via newspapers, radio, TV, and the internet.<ref name=\"Country Fire Authority\">{{cite web|date=2020|url=https://cdn.cfa.vic.gov.au/documents/20143/80821/Fire-Danger-Ratings-Brochure-Apr-2017.pdf/b253d413-aa46-600c-e529-e4f9e12fe36f|title=Fire Danger Rating Brochure|agency=[[Country Fire Authority]]|publisher=Government of Victoria|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, a standardised ''Fire Danger Rating'' (FDR) was adopted by all Australian states. This included a whole new level \u2013 catastrophic fire danger. The first time this level of danger was forecast for Sydney was in November 2019 during the 2019\u20132020 bushfire season.<ref>{{cite news|author=Cox, Lisa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/nov/11/catastrophic-fire-danger-what-does-it-mean-and-and-what-should-we-do-in-these-conditions|title=Catastrophic fire danger: what does it mean and what should we do in these conditions?|work=Guardian Australia|date=11 November 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> In 2010, following a national review of the bush fire danger ratings, new trigger points for each rating were introduced for grassland areas in most jurisdictions.\n\n<!--The colours in the following table are based on the Fire Danger Rating at the CFS website, http://www.cfs.sa.gov.au/site/fire_restrictions/fire_bans.jsp -->\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Fire Danger Rating\n|-\n!Category\n!Fire Danger Index\n|-\n|style = \"background:#C80815\" | '''Catastrophic / Code Red'''\n|Forest 100+ Grass 150+\n|-\n|style = \"background:#FF4040\" | '''Extreme'''\n|Forest 75\u2013100 Grass 100\u2013150\n|-\n|style = \"background:orange\" | '''Severe'''\n|Forest 50\u201375 Grass 50\u2013100\n|-\n|style = \"background:#FCF75E\" | '''Very high'''\n|25\u201350\n|-\n|style = \"background:skyblue\" | '''High'''\n|12\u201325\n|-\n|style = \"background:#ADDFAD\" | '''Low to moderate'''\n|0\u201312\n|}\n\n==Remote monitoring==\n[[Wildfire#Detection|Remote monitoring of wildfires]] is done in Australia. Geoscience Australia developed the (real-time) Sentinel bushfire monitoring system. It uses data from satellites to help fire-fighting agencies assess and manage risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-11/real-time-bushfire-monitoring-system-to-be-developed/6688510|title=Real-time bushfire monitoring satellite system to be developed in Australia|date=11 August 2015|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csiro.au/en/Research/Astronomy/Earth-observation/Sentinel-hotspots|title=Bushfire tracking with Sentinel Hotspots|website=www.csiro.au}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sentinel.ga.gov.au/|title=Sentinel Hotspots|website=sentinel.ga.gov.au}}</ref> There is also MyFireWatch, which is a program based on an existing Department of Fire and Emergency Services (DFES) program, redeveloped by Landgate and Edith Cowan University (ECU) for use by the general public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-09-28/myfirewatch-brings-bushfire-information-to-wa-outback/5772860|title=Better bushfire information for regional communities|first=Natasha|last=Harradine|date=28 September 2014|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myfirewatch.landgate.wa.gov.au/|title=MyFireWatch \u2013 Bushfire map information Australia|website=myfirewatch.landgate.wa.gov.au}}</ref>\nBesides the use of satellites, Australian firefighters also make use of [[UAV]]'s as a tool for combating fire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/news/drones-to-assist-firefighters-in-emergencies/|title=Drones to assist firefighters in emergencies|website=NSW Government}}</ref>\n\n== Regional management ==\nThe [[Australasian Fire Authorities Council]] (AFAC) is the peak body responsible for representing fire, emergency services, and land management agencies in the Australasian region.\n\n=== Queensland ===\nThe Rural Fire Service (RFS) is a volunteer-based firefighting agency and operates as part of the [[Queensland Fire and Emergency Services]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruralfire.qld.gov.au/|title=Rural Fire Service Queensland}}</ref>\n\n=== New South Wales ===\n[[Fire and Rescue NSW]] (FRNSW), the Forestry Corporation of NSW (FCNSW), the [[National Parks and Wildlife Service (New South Wales)|National Parks and Wildlife Service]] (NPWS) and the [[New South Wales Rural Fire Service]] (RFS) work together to manage and respond to fires across New South Wales.\n\n=== South Australia ===\nThe [[Country Fire Service]] is a volunteer-based fire service in the state of South Australia. The CFS operates as a part of the [[South Australian Fire and Emergency Services Commission]] (SAFECOM).\n\n=== Victoria ===\n[[File:Major Victorian bushfires in the 2000s.PNG|thumb|right|Major bushfires in Victoria in the 2000s]]\n{{main|Bushfires in Victoria}}\n\nIn Victoria, the [[Country Fire Authority]] (CFA) provides firefighting and other emergency services to country areas and regional townships within the state, as well as large portions of the outer suburban areas and growth corridors of [[Melbourne]] not covered by the [[Metropolitan Fire Brigade (Melbourne)|Metropolitan Fire Brigade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/|title=Country Fire Authority|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nResponsibility for fire suppression and management, including planned burning on public land such as State Forests and National Parks, which makes up about 7.1 million hectares or about one-third of the State, sits with the [[Department of Environment, Land, Water, and Planning|Department of Environment, Land, Water, and Planning (DELWP)]].\n\n=== Western Australia ===\nThe [[Department of Fire and Emergency Services]] (DFES) and the [[Department of Parks and Wildlife (Western Australia)|Department of Parks and Wildlife]] (P&W) have joint responsibility for bushfire management in Western Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfes.wa.gov.au/|title=Welcome to DFES|work= Department of Fire and Emergency Services of Western Australia|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref> DFES is an umbrella organisation supporting the Fire and Rescue Service (FRS), Bush Fire Service (BFS), Volunteer Fire and Rescue Service (VFRS), State Emergency Service (SES), Volunteer Fire and Emergency Service (VFES), Emergency Services Cadets and the Volunteer Marine Rescue Service (VMR).\n\n=== Tasmania ===\nThe [[Tasmania Fire Service]] manages bushfires in Tasmania with the help of [[Tasmanian Parks and Wildlife Service]] and [[Forestry Tasmania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fire.tas.gov.au/Show?pageId=colAbout |publisher=Tasmania Fire Service |title=About TFS |year=2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.dpac.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/208131/1.Tasmanian_Bushfires_Inquiry_Report.pdf |isbn=978-0-9923581-0-5 |title=2013 Tasmanian Bushfires Inquiry: Volume 1}}</ref>\n\n== Guidelines for survival ==\nLocal authorities provide education and information for residents in bushfire-prone regions regarding the location of current fires,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/fires-near-me | title= NSW Current Fires | publisher= NSW Rural Fire Service }}</ref> preservation of life and property<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/2933/BushFireSurvivalPlan.pdf | title=How to survive a bushfire | accessdate=20 February 2017 | publisher= NSW Rural Fire Service }}</ref> and when to escape by car.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.driverknowledgetests.com/resources/how-to-drive-through-a-bushfire/ | title=Driving in a bushfire | accessdate=20 February 2017 | date=13 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Major bushfires in Australia ==\n{{main|List of major bushfires in Australia}}\nBushfires have accounted for over 800 deaths in Australia since 1851 and, in 2012, the total accumulated cost was estimated at $1.6&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://romseyaustralia.com/firesum.html|title=Summary of Major Bush Fires in Australia Since 1851|accessdate=29 October 2010|work=Romsey Australia}}</ref> In terms of monetary cost however, they rate behind the damage caused by drought, [[storm|severe storms]], [[hail]], and [[cyclone]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ema.gov.au/ema/emadisasters.nsf/webEventsByCategory?OpenView&Start=1&Count=30&Expand=1#1|title=EMA Disasters Database|work=Emergency management Australia|accessdate=30 October 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20101118000000/http://www.ema.gov.au/ema/emadisasters.nsf/webEventsByCategory?OpenView&Start=1&Count=30&Expand=1#1|archive-date=18 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> perhaps because they most commonly occur outside highly populated urban areas.  However, the severe fires of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|summer of 2019\u20132020]] affected densely populated areas including holiday destinations leading NSW Rural Fire Services Commissioner, Shane Fitzsimmons, to claim it was \"absolutely\" the worst bushfire season on record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/extraordinary-2019-ends-with-deadliest-day-of-the-worst-fire-season-20191231-p53nw0.html|title='Extraordinary' 2019 ends with deadliest day of the worst fire season|author1=Alexander, Harriet|author2=Chung, Laura|author3=Chrysanthos, Natassia|author4=Drevikovsky, Janek|author5=Brickwood, James|date=1 January 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Australia}}\n* [[Aerial firefighting and forestry in southern Australia]]\n* [[AS3959]]\n* [[List of Australian bushfire seasons]]\n* [[List of major bushfires in Australia]]\n* [[List of natural disasters in Australia]]\n* [[McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index]]\n* [[Pyrotron]], a device designed to help firefighters better understand how to combat the rapid spread of bush fires\n* [[Wildfires in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<ref>\u201cAustralia Fires: A Visual Guide to the Bushfire Crisis.\u201d BBC News, BBC, 31 January 2020, www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-50951043.\n</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.bom.gov.au/weather-services/fire-weather-centre/bushfire-weather/index.shtml Bureau of Meteorology]\n\n{{Wildland Firefighting}}\n{{Bushfires in Australia}}\n{{Australian Fire Services}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bushfires In Australia}}\n[[Category:Bushfires in Australia| ]]\n", "name_user": "194.103.3.252", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bushfires_in_Australia"}
