ttlement-->\n| native_name = \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a\n| official_name = Kalinovik\n| other_name = \n| image_skyline = Kalinovik - mestecko na nahorni plosine (1153 m.n.m).jpg\n| image_caption = View on Kalinovik\n| settlement_type = [[List of cities in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Town]] and [[Municipalities of Republika Srpska|municipality]]\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name = {{Flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Entity]]\n| subdivision_name1 = {{Flag|Republika Srpska}}\n| subdivision_type2 = \n| subdivision_name2 = \n| timezone = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset = +1\n| timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +2\n| unit_pref = Metric\n| map_caption = Location of Kalinovik within Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| image_shield =\n| image_map = Kalinovik municipality.svg\n| area_blank1_title = Town\n| area_blank1_km2 = \n| area_blank2_title = Municipality\n| area_blank2_km2 = 681.15\n| population_as_of = 2013 census\n| population_blank1_title = Town\n| population_blank1 = 1093\n| population_density_blank1_km2 = auto\n| population_blank2_title = Municipality\n| population_blank2 = 2029\n| population_density_blank2_km2 = auto\n| coordinates = {{coord|43|30|15|N|18|26|48|E|region:BA_type:city|display=inline, title}}\n| area_code = 57\n| website = {{url|http://kalinovik.info/}}\n| footnotes = \n| leader_title = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name = Mileva Komlenovi\u0107\n| leader_party = [[Serb Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|SDS]]\n}}\n'''Kalinovik''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a}}) is a town and municipality located in [[Republika Srpska]], an entity of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. As of 2013, the town has a population of 1,093 inhabitants, while the municipality has 2,029 inhabitants.\n\nThe municipality adjoins the municipality of [[Konjic]], with which the boundary also forms part of the Inter-Entity Boundary Line (IEBL) between the two constituent entities of Bosnia and Herzegovina.\n\n==Geography==\nKalinovik is located about 70 kilometres south of [[Sarajevo]], in the middle of one of the [[Karstic]] landscapes characteristic of the region. The calcareous plateaus, eaten into by water, are strewn with valleys or fields, types of [[sinkhole]]-like lunar craters.<ref>http://www.nato.int/sfor/indexinf/125/p02a/t0102a.htm</ref>\n\nThe municipality adjoins the municipality of [[Konjic]].  The towns of Konjic and Kalinovik are connected by an asphalt road.  Communications were disrupted when the bridge over the [[Ljuta]] river at [[Dindo, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Dindo]] was destroyed in autumn 1995, in the last months of the war, but were restored after a replacement bridge was constructed in 2002.<ref>http://www.nato.int/sfor/indexinf/146/p12a/t02p12a.htm</ref>\n\nThe boundary between the municipalities of Konjic and Kalinovik also forms part of the Inter-Entity Boundary Line (IEBL) between the two constituent entities of Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>http://www.nato.int/sfor/indexinf/150/p08a/t02p08a.htm SFOR Informer #150, October 24, 2002</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nClimate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] subtype for this climate is \"[[K\u00f6ppen climate classification#GROUP C: Mild Temperate/mesothermal climates|Cfb]]\" (Marine West Coast Climate/[[Oceanic climate]]).\n{{Weather box\n|location = Kalinovik\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 24\n|Feb high F = 23\n|Mar high F = 28\n|Apr high F = 32\n|May high F = 42\n|Jun high F = 48\n|Jul high F = 53\n|Aug high F = 53\n|Sep high F = 48\n|Oct high F = 41\n|Nov high F = 31\n|Dec high F = 26\n|year high F = 37\n|Jan low F = 8\n|Feb low F = 18\n|Mar low F = 22\n|Apr low F = 27\n|May low F = 36\n|Jun low F = 41\n|Jul low F = 46\n|Aug low F = 46\n|Sep low F = 42\n|Oct low F = 34\n|Nov low F = 26\n|Dec low F = 20\n|year low F = 31\n|Jan precipitation days = 15\n|Feb precipitation days = 15\n|Mar precipitation days = 15\n|Apr precipitation days = 16\n|May precipitation days = 14\n|Jun precipitation days = 12\n|Jul precipitation days = 10\n|Aug precipitation days = 11\n|Sep precipitation days = 9\n|Oct precipitation days = 12\n|Nov precipitation days = 13\n|Dec precipitation days = 14\n|year precipitation days = 156\n|source 1 = Weatherbase <ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web\n|url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=25331&cityname=Kalinoyik-\n|publisher=Weatherbase\n|title=Weatherbase.com\n|year=2013\n}}\nRetrieved on July 13, 2013.\n</ref>\n|date=July 2013\n}}\n\n==History==\n===Bosnian War===\nBetween April 1992 and April 1993 during the first year of the [[Bosnian War]] the municipality of Kalinovik [[Bosniak]] population left Kalinovik, moving into Bosnian forces controlling areas. Grave crimes were committed against Bosniak Muslim civilians in Kalinovik by the Bosnian Serbs Ratko Bundalo and Nedjo Zeljaja.<ref>http://www.unhchr.ch/tbs/doc.nsf/0/333378630589b6d680256674005bc280?opendocument</ref>\n\nBundalo was commander of the Tactical Group in Kalinovik and Zeljaja was commander of the Public Safety Station.  Under their authority civilians were detained in the \"Miladin Radojevic\" school building in 1992.  Members of paramilitary units who \"mistreated all residents, irrespective of ethnicity\" took part in the rape of women and other physical abuse of detainees in the school. Men prisoners were taken out and beaten, and some never returned.  Aleksandar Cerovina and Slavko Lalovi\u0107 were mentioned by witnesses as accomplices in the crimes and Cerovina as having been involved in intimidation of witnesses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bim.ba/en/146/10/15560/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722062121/http://www.bim.ba/en/146/10/15560/ |archive-date=2011-07-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2009 the Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina found Bundalo and Zeljaja guilty of persecution, murder, detention and torture of Muslims from April 1992 to March 1993. Bundalo was sentenced to 19 years in prison, Zeljaja to 15 years. A third defendant. Djordjislav Askraba, director of the Barutni Magacin detention camp, was acquitted due to lack of evidence.<ref>http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/newsbriefs/setimes/newsbriefs/2009/12/22/nb-09</ref>\n\nIn autumn 1995 the Bosnian Army destroyed the bridge over the [[Ljuta]] river at [[Dindo, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Dindo]] to prevent [[Bosnian Serb]] tanks attacking Konjic and the [[Neretva valley]].  The road link between the towns of Konjic and Kalinovik was restored in 2002 when a Bailey Bridge across the river was constructed by a Spanish army engineering section of [[SFOR]] in a [[UNHCR]]-led initiative.<ref>http://www.nato.int/sfor/indexinf/146/p12a/t02p12a.htm</ref>\n\n===Post-war social developments===\nThere is unemployment and rural deprivation in Kalinovik.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/4741682.stm</ref>\nThe Upper Drina valley, devastated by the war and bisected by the inter-entity boundary, remains troubled by deep-seated divisions and difficult community relations.  Political obstruction by hard-line politicians has isolated the area from international development assistance and the economic mainstream.  Core economic problems are exacerbated by geographical remoteness and the mountainous region is peripheral to regional and national markets.  Many local communities are among the most deprived in Bosnia.<ref>http://www.undp.ba/index.aspx?PID=21&RID=81</ref>\n\nThe war crimes indictee and fugitive Ratko Mladi\u0107 remains an influential presence locally.  Friends and family still express support for him and regard him as a hero though local people are reluctant to talk to outsiders.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/4741682.stm</ref>  Serbian officials have said that comrades from Kalinovik are among Mladi\u0107's support network.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/27/AR2006032701498_2.html</ref>\n\nOnce a prosperous [[Austro-Hungarian]] military stronghold, Kalinovik is now an impoverished rural municipality with a population of only 2,500. During the [[Bosnian war]] the area was ethnically cleansed of its Bosniak (Muslim) population by the Bosnian Serb authorities.  Many of its Serb inhabitants have since left in search of better lives elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://operations.ifad.org/web/guest/country/voice/tags/bosnia%20and%20herzegovina/women_skills |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231172242/http://operations.ifad.org/web/guest/country/voice/tags/bosnia%20and%20herzegovina/women_skills |archive-date=2010-12-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/4741682.stm</ref>\n\nNewcomers from Sarajevo have settled in the town.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/4741682.stm</ref>  The traditional domestic role of women in Kalinovik has changed since Verica Elez, a professor of Serbian language and literature and an newcomer, began to encourage local women to take advantage of the post-war development opportunities offered by international organizations concerned with women\u2019s issues and with strengthening the role of women in rural communities.  The women\u2019s group she is president of collaborates with NGOs to obtain computers, develop marketing opportunities and encourage women to take on management roles. The NGO IFAD has supported development in Kalinovik through rural infrastructure reconstruction, credit for livestock, and training and seminars. Some women are involved in wool processing (weaving and scarf and blanket making) and are planning a weaving workshop, others work in milk collection and processing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://operations.ifad.org/web/guest/country/voice/tags/bosnia%20and%20herzegovina/women_skills |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231172242/http://operations.ifad.org/web/guest/country/voice/tags/bosnia%20and%20herzegovina/women_skills |archive-date=2010-12-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Settlements==\nAside from the town of Kalinovik, the municipality includes the following settlements:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Bak, Kalinovik|Bak]]\n* [[Boji\u0107i]]\n* [[Boljanovi\u0107i, Kalinovik|Boljanovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Borija]]\n* [[Bo\u017eanovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Brda, Kalinovik|Brda]]\n* [[Bukvica]]\n* [[Cerova, Kalinovik|Cerova]]\n* [[\u010cestaljevo]]\n* [[Daganj]]\n* [[Dobro Polje]]\n* [[Dragomili\u0107i]]\n* [[Dubrava, Kalinovik|Dubrava]]\n* [[Gapi\u0107i]]\n* [[Golubi\u0107i, Kalinovik|Golubi\u0107i]]\n* [[Gradina, Kalinovik|Gradina]]\n* [[Graiselji\u0107i]]\n* [[Gvozno]]\n* [[Hotovlje, Kalinovik|Hotovlje]]\n* [[Hrelji\u0107i]]\n* [[Jablani\u0107i]]\n* [[Ja\u017ei\u0107i]]\n* [[Jela\u0161ca, Kalinovik|Jela\u0161ca]]\n* [[Jezero, Kalinovik|Jezero]]\n* [[Klinja]]\n* [[Kolakovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Kova\u010di\u0107i, Kalinovik|Kova\u010di\u0107i]]\n* [[Krbljine]]\n* [[Kru\u0161\u010dica, Kalinovik|Kru\u0161\u010dica]]\n* [[Kuta, Kalinovik|Kuta]]\n* [[Kutine]]\n* [[Luko]]\n* [[Ljusi\u0107i]]\n* [[Ljuta, Kalinovik|Ljuta]]\n* [[Meko\u010da]]\n* [[Mjehovina]]\n* [[Mosorovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Mu\u0161i\u0107i, Kalinovik|Mu\u0161i\u0107i]]\n* [[Nedavi\u0107]]\n* [[Obadi, Kalinovik|Obadi]]\n* [[Obalj]]\n* [[Obrnja]]\n* [[Osija]]\n* [[Pla\u010dikus]]\n* [[Plo\u010dnik, Kalinovik|Plo\u010dnik]]\n* [[Polje, Kalinovik|Polje]]\n* [[Popovi\u0107i, Kalinovik|Popovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Porija]]\n* [[Presjedovac]]\n* [[Rajac, Kalinovik|Rajac]]\n* [[Rastovac, Kalinovik|Rastovac]]\n* [[Ru\u0111ice]]\n* [[Sela, Kalinovik|Sela]]\n* [[Sijer\u010da]]\n* [[So\u010dani]]\n* [[Strane, Kalinovik|Strane]]\n* [[Susje\u010dno]]\n* [[\u0160ivolji]]\n* [[Tmu\u0161e]]\n* [[Tomi\u0161lja]]\n* [[Tre\u0161njevica, Kalinovik|Tre\u0161njevica]]\n* [[Trnovica, Kalinovik|Trnovica]]\n* [[Tuhobi\u0107, Kalinovik|Tuhobi\u0107]]\n* [[Ulog]]\n* [[Unukovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Varizi]]\n* [[Varo\u0161, Kalinovik|Varo\u0161]]\n* [[Vihovi\u0107i, Kalinovik|Vihovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Vlaholje]]\n* [[Vrhovina, Kalinovik|Vrhovina]]\n* [[Vujinovi\u0107i]]\n* [[Zelomi\u0107i]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n| type = \n| percentages = pagr\n|1953|13774 |1961|7319 |1971|9458 |1981|6597 |1991|4249 |2013|2029\n}}\nAccording to the 2013 census results, the municipality of Kalinovik has 2,029 inhabitants.\n\n===Ethnic groups===\nThe ethnic composition of the municipality:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Ethnic group\n! Population<br>1971\n! Population<br>1991<ref name=\"popis2013\">{{cite web |title=Popis 2013 u BiH \u2013 Fo\u010da |url=http://www.statistika.ba/?show=12&id=20613 |website=statistika.ba |accessdate=29 December 2018 |language=Bosnian}}</ref>\n! Population<br>2013<ref name=\"popis2013\" />\n|-\n|[[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serbs]]\n|align=\"right\"|5,536\n|align=\"right\"|2,814\n|align=\"right\"|1,947\n|-\n|[[Bosniaks]]/[[Muslims (nationality)|Muslims]]\n|align=\"right\"|3,796\n|align=\"right\"|1,314\n|align=\"right\"|57\n|-\n|[[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Croats]]\n|align=\"right\"|44\n|align=\"right\"|17\n|align=\"right\"|8\n|-\n|Others\n|align=\"right\"|82\n|align=\"right\"|104\n|align=\"right\"|17\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|'''Total'''\n|align=\"right\"|9,458\n|align=\"right\"|4,249\n|align=\"right\"|2,029\n|}\n\n==Economy==\nThe following table gives a preview of total number of registered people employed in legal entities per their core activity (as of 2018):<ref name=\"stats2018\">{{cite web |title=Cities and Municipalities of Republika Srpska |url=http://www2.rzs.rs.ba/static/uploads/bilteni/gradovi_i_opstine_republike_srpske/2019/Gradovi_I_Opstine_Republike_Srpske_2019_WEB.pd